11. Bg5 { mistake } { [%cal Gf4g5] } (11. Be2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nfd7 13. Qa3 e5 14. dxe5 Re8 15. O-O Qe7 16. Qxe7 Rxe7 17. e6 Rxe6 18. Bg4 Re7 $14) 11... Na4 { Brilliant move that the latest engine technology approves } (11... h6 12. Bh4 (12. Be3 Nfd7 13. Qb4 Be6 14. h3 $10) 12... Re8 13. Be2 g5 14. Bg3 $10) (11... Nfd7 12. Bxe7 (12. Qxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxe7 Rfe8 14. Bg5 f5 $10) 12... Nxc5 13. Bxd8 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Raxd8 $17) 12. Qa3 (12. Nxa4 Nxe4 13. Bxe7 (13. Qxe7 Qa5+ (13... Nxg5 14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Nxg5 Rfe8+ 16. Kd2 Bxd1 17. Kxd1 Rxd4+ 18. Kc2 Rxa4) 14. b4 Qxa4 15. Qxe4 Rfe8 16. Be7 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Bf8 18. Be2 Rxe7 $17) (13. Qc1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Qxa4 $17) (13. Qb4 Nxg5 14. Nxg5 Bxd1 15. Kxd1 b5 16. Nc5 Bxd4 17. Kc2 a5 18. Qa3 Qd5 19. Nce4 h6 20. Qb3 hxg5 $17) (13. Qc2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nxg5 15. Bg2 Qd5 16. O-O Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 (17. Kh1 Qh5 18. h3 Nxd4 $17) 17... Qxf3 $17) 13... Re8 (13... Qc7 14. Qa3 (14. Bd6 Nxd6 15. Be2 Rfe8 16. Kf1 b6 $17) 14... Rfe8 15. Bb4 Ng3+ 16. Kd2 Nxh1 $17) 14. Bxd8 Nxc5+ 15. Be2 Nxa4 $17 16. Bg5 Nxb2 $17) 12... Nxc3 { Counter intuitive - it seems to be strengthening the center but creates more weaknesses actually exploitable } 13. bxc3 (13. Qxc3 Nxe4 14. Qc1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qa5+ 16. Bd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Qxa2 $17) 13... Nxe4 14. Bxe7 (14. Be2 Nxg5 15. Nxg5 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 e5 17. h4 exd4 $17 18. cxd4 Qd5 $17) 14... Qb6 (14... Qd5 { is possibly more accurate } 15. c4 (15. Bxf8 Bxf8 16. Qb3 Qxb3 17. axb3 Re8 18. Bc4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nxc3+ 20. Kd2 Nxd1 21. Rxd1 a6 $17) 15... Qe6 16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. c5 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Nc3+ 19. Qe3 Nxd1 20. Qxe6 fxe6 21. Kxd1 Rd8 22. Bd3 Rxd4 $17) 15. Bc4 (15. Bxf8 Bxf8 16. Qb3 Nxc3 17. Qxb6 (17. Qxc3 Bb4 $17) 17... axb6 18. Ra1 Bb4 $17 19. Bd3 Nxa2+ 20. Kf1 Bc3 $17) 15... Nxc3 16. Bc5 (16. Qxc3 Rae8 17. O-O Rxe7 $17) (16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. Qc1 Nxd1 18. Qxd1 Qb4+ 19. Kf1 Qxc4+ $17) 16... Rfe8+ 17. Kf1 Be6 (17... Qc7 18. Qxc3 b6 19. Ba3 c5 20. h3 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Bxd1 22. Nf3 Bxf3 23. Bb2 Qe5 24. Qxe5 Rxe5 25. Bxe5 $16) 18. Bxb6 (18. Bxe6 { 6 is a forced mate in } 18... Qb5+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Ng3+ 21. Kg1 Qf1+ 22. Rxf1 Ne2#) (18. Bb3 Qb5+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Ng3+ 21. Kg1 Qf1+ 22. Rxf1 Ne2#) (18. Qxc3 Qxc5 19. dxc5 Bxc3 20. Bxe6 Rxe6 $17) 18... Bxc4+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Nxd4+ { This tactical scenario, where a king is repeatedly revealed to checks, is sometimes called a "windmill." } 21. Kg1 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nc3+ 23. Kg1 axb6 24. Qb4 Ra4 25. Qxb6 Nxd1 26. h3 Rxa2 27. Kh2 Nxf2 28. Re1 Rxe1 29. Qd8+ Bf8 30. Nxe1 Bd5 31. Nf3 Ne4 32. Qb8 b5 { Every piece and pawn of the black camp is defended.The white queen has nothing to do. } 33. h4 h5 (33... b4 34. h5 b3 35. Kh3 gxh5 $17) 34. Ne5 Kg7 35. Kg1 (35. Qc7 Bd6 $17) 35... Bc5+ 36. Kf1 Ng3+ { Now Byrne is hopelessly entangled in Fischer's mating net. } 37. Ke1 Bb4+ 38. Kd1 Bb3+ 39. Kc1 Ne2+ 40. Kb1 Nc3+ 41. Kc1 Rc2# { 0 0 The Game of the Century is a chess game that was won by the 13-year-old future world champion Bobby Fischer against Donald Byrne in the Rosenwald Memorial Tournament at the Marshall Chess Club in New York City on October 17, 1956.In Chess Review, Hans Kmoch dubbed it "The Game of the Century" and wrote: "The following game, a stunning masterpiece of combination play performed by a boy of 13 against a formidable opponent, matches the finest on record in the history of chess prodigies Engine verdict Robert James Fischer 0 Inaccuracies 0 Mistakes 0 Blunders 5 Average centipawn loss 98% Accuracy } 0-1


