[Event "Carlsen-Karjakin World Chess Championship"]
[Site "New York NY USA"]
[Date "2016.11.14"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 3 - 14th Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/x4jTEm1L"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 { Magnus chooses now 1.e4 contrasting from 1.d4 in Game 1 Kingscrusher Game 3 video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=It0Y1dfO9Yg } 1... e5 { Sergey replies classically } 2. Nf3 { Attacking the e5 pawn } 2... Nc6 { Defending the e5 pawn } 3. Bb5 { The classic Ruy Lopez - a frequent visitor in World chess championship matches } 3... Nf6 { The Berlin Defence - a very solid option } 4. O-O { The most popular move. White is not concerned about the e4 pawn being taken here. } 4... Nxe4 { This is black's most popular option. } 5. Re1 { The 2nd most popular move. The most popular continuation is d4. Re1 not only potentially hits e5 but also vacates f1 for the bishop on b5 to retreat to. } (5. d4 { The most popular continuation } 5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 { This start position has been "all the range" in World championship matches in recent years. Black has the bishop pair, but has doubled pawns and a less than ideal King position. However it has become very trendy in recent years. One source of the surge of popularity for the rise of the Berlin was Vladimir Kramnik's match against Kasparov where this opening was employed very successfully and neutralised Kasparov. }) 5... Nd6 { Hitting the bishop on b5. Karjakin has been white against Carlsen in this position in 2013 - which ended in a draw. } 6. Nxe5 { The most popular move. Bxc6 instead offers White very little and statistically in master games shows great tendency for great results with Black. } (6. Bxc6?! { Although tempting this scores very badly for White in practice. } 6... dxc6 7. Nxe5 Be7 8. d4 O-O { Black has fully equalised here. }) 6... Be7 { Shielding the king and preparing to castle } 7. Bf1 { Safeguarding the bishop } 7... Nxe5 { By far the most popular move here. Putting the rook on e5 faciliates a later tempo gain with Bf6. This is much more popular than the 2nd used choice which is Nf5. } (7... Nf5!? { A viable alternative from a theoretical perspective. } 8. Nf3 O-O 9. d4 d5 { There have been quite a few master games from this position including Carlsen vs Anand in 2010 which resulted in a draw. } 10. c3) 8. Rxe5 O-O { There is only one shared file in this position. In principle the excitement levels would seem to be fairly contained for the dynamic prospects of this position. } 9. d4 { The most popular move here where White has had some success but where there is a high percentage of draws as well in master games. This is testimony to the solid nature of the opening here. } 9... Bf6 { Gaining a tempo on the rook and putting pressure on White's d4 central square. } 10. Re2!? { The first theoretical suprise! Much more usual is Re1. This almost looks like some sort of "mouse slip" and one might think so if it was a lichess bullet game :). However here it may be the product of deep preparation. The move takes the game out of well trodden theoretical territory but not entirely unknown. It featured in the high level game Rustam Kasimdzhanov ( a GM and former FIDE world chess champion) vs Hrant Melkumyan : Bundesliga (2015/16). In this game black later played b6 and Nb7 with d5 and Nd6 to follow. This stem game ended in a draw. } { [%cal Ge4e1] } 10... b6 { It seems very tempting to have some options like Ba6 to hit the rook here. But this does represent a commitment of pawn structure. Quite often as well the bishop on c8 is supporting ideas like g6 and Nf5. So it seems one upside of Re2 is actually provoking b6 for Ba6 with the idea of perhaps having a little greater effectiveness for a later Bd3 from White to pressurise the b1-h7 diagonal with. } { [%csl Bc8,Yf5][%cal Yc8a6,Bc8f5,Be2e1,Yf1d3,Bd3h7] } 11. Re1 { The rook has apparently "done its job" in provoking b6. But the question now is if it really is enough for White to be able to create a significant advantage. } 11... Re8 { Black seems to threaten now Rxe1 followed by Bxd4. } 12. Bf4 { A very resourceful way of parrying black's threat of winning the d pawn. Now winning the d pawn is ruled out tactically. } 12... Rxe1 13. Qxe1 Qe7! { Black does not take the bait on d4. This would be taking a "poisoned pawn". } (13... Bxd4? { This would be a very bad mistake leading to a big advantage for White in all variations. } 14. Bxd6 { This represents a very big advantage for White. It doesn't just double black pawns - it also weakens the e4 square making way for the powerful Qe4 in some lines. } 14... cxd6 (14... Bxb2 15. Bxc7 { Exploiting the back row weakness. } 15... Qf8 (15... Qxc7?? 16. Qe8#) 16. Nd2 Bxa1 17. Qxa1 Bb7 18. Be5 f6 19. Bd4 { White has a very big advantage here. }) 15. Qe4 { Double attacking a8 and d4 } { [%cal Ge4a8,Ge4d4] } 15... Bxb2 (15... Qf6 16. Qe8#) 16. Qxa8 { White has a big advantage in all variations here. } 16... Bxa1 17. Ba6 { [%cal Ga8d8] } 17... Kf8 18. Bxc8 { A piece up for White. } (18. Qxc8 Qxc8 19. Bxc8 { A piece up for White. })) 14. Nc3 { White now has the threat of Nd5 } 14... Bb7! { Parrying the Nd5 threat and also strengthening the back row. } (14... Qxe1?! 15. Rxe1 Bxd4?? (15... Bb7 16. Bxd6 cxd6 { This would be a wretched pawn structure for black. White is a clear advantage here. } 17. Nb5 d5 18. c3 { White is significantly better here. }) 16. Bxd6 cxd6 17. Re8#) 15. Qxe7 Bxe7 16. a4 { A very interesting move. Not only it supports the immediate a5 idea - it also means that in some future endgames, the rook on a1 might activate via the a3 square. This is especially important in this type of position because there is only one shared file - the 'e' file. Another point of potential infiltration via a3 could be very handy. } 16... a6 { Black parries the threat of a5 from White. Now a5 is rendered less effective. } 17. g3 { A very interesting move which some major aspects to it. The first aspect is trying to weaken black on the light squares with a later Bg2. In particular it might be nice to first exchange off the light squared bishops and then pounce with Nd5, in which case it would be sometimes difficult for black to evict a knight from d5 given that c6 would run into Nxb6. But the other major aspet of g3 is that it also facilitates Bh3 hitting the d7 pawn. If the a8 rook has to comit to d8 then Re1 can sometimes be extra effective. } (17. a5?! b5! { This would keep things closed and solid. }) 17... g5 { A very energetic forcing move but one which carries some structural commitment behind it. The f5 square can potentially become weak especially if the light squared bishops are exchanged off. } 18. Bxd6! { Giving up the dark squared bishop seems the only interesting way to proceed here. The game is starting to be slightly imbalanced. Black has the classic bishop pair, but has some extra structural commitments - especially the weakened f5 square. } (18. Bd2?! { Both bd2 and be3 don't help White much. } 18... Bf6 { Black is doing well in this position } 19. Bd3 Re8 20. Be3 Kg7 { Black would have more than equalised here. }) (18. Be3?! f5 19. Bg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 c6 { Parrying Nd5 threat } 21. d5 Nc4 22. Nd1 Bf6 { Black is doing very well here - more than equalised. }) (18. Bc1?! Re8 { White has nothing better than Be3 here. } 19. Be3) 18... Bxd6 19. Bg2 { Trying to immediately remove black's bishop pair. Additionally exchanging off light squared bishops is a great way traditionally of trying to exploit weakened light squares. } 19... Bxg2 (19... c6?! { This would lead to a very passive position. } 20. a5 b5 21. Ne4 Be7 22. Nc5 Bc8 23. Nd3 { White would have an annoying bind here. Yes black would preserve the bishop pair - but at some cost. }) 20. Kxg2 f5 { Black neutralises the potential threat of Ne4. It also facilitates Kf7 } 21. Nd5 Kf7 { Neutralising the potential Nf6+ threat winning d7 and also facilitates Kf6 is the f5 pawn needs protection. } 22. Ne3 Kf6 (22... f4!? { This may be a reasonable alternative to the game continuation but does represent a greater structural comitment than simply defending the pawn with Kf6. } 23. Nc4 (23. Nf5 fxg3 24. hxg3 { This position although showing the knight on a nice square might not be significant for any kind of winning advantage. }) 23... fxg3 24. hxg3 h5 25. Rh1 { White has a tiny advantage here. }) 23. Nc4 { It looks at first sight entirely undesirable for black to allow Nxd6 which seems to wreck black's pawn structure. } { [%cal Gc4d6] } 23... Bf8?! { Re8 instead seems to lead to a completely drawn rook and pawn endgame if White takes on d6. The proof really seems to be in the pudding. Whilst visually Nxd6 seems to cause a wreck for black's pawn structure, there are in fact very limited infiltration opportunities. One key one of Ra3 seems to fall short as the variations show. However from a spectator and commentator perspective, Bf8 is a welcome delight as it keeps things imbalanced and with greater tension. } (23... Re8!? 24. Nxd6 cxd6 { [%cal Ga1a3,Ga3b3,Gb3b6] } 25. Ra3 { This position seems in fact very drawish. The problem here is that if White plays d5 then the e5 square can be used by black's king. Given this is the case, this entire continuation may have been the most straightforward way for black to have achieved a draw. } 25... Rc8 26. Rb3 Rc6! 27. d5?! { [%cal Gf6e5] } 27... Rxc2 28. Rxb6 Ke5 29. b3 Rb2 30. Rxa6 Rxb3 31. Ra7 Ra3 32. Rxd7 Rxa4 33. Rxh7 g4 34. Rh5 Ra1 { Very drawish indeed! }) 24. Re1 (24. Ne5 { Hitting d7 but this is not a great issue. Black can even just play Bd6 as well as Rd8 } 24... Bd6 (24... Rd8 25. c3 Bd6 26. f4 (26. Nc4 Re8 { Again this is entirely possible for black to do. Taking on d6 although structurally desirable does not lead to any effective infiltration opportunities. }) 26... gxf4 27. gxf4 Rg8+ 28. Kf3 Bxe5 29. fxe5+ Ke6 { With a very drawish rook and pawn endgame. }) 25. Nxd7+ Ke6 26. Ne5 Bxe5 27. Re1 Rd8 28. Rxe5+ Kf6 29. c3 c5 30. Re3 cxd4 31. Rd3 Ke5 { With a very drawish rook and pawn endgame. }) 24... Rd8?! { Protecting the d7 pawn ahead of Ne5. This means that simply Bd6 can now be played in the event of Ne5. } { Karjakin stated after the game that he was unhappy with this move, and that Carlsen's next move was very strong. } 25. f4! { Fixes the f5 pawn and secures more the e5 potential knight outpost. In the event of g4 then White has some extra options like h3 with potentially using the h file later with Rh1 etc. } { While the engines would mislead the viewer into thinking that this is boringly equal, in fact the situation is extremely challenging for Black. From a practical point of view, Karjakin was faced with the choice of gxf4, g4, or h6. When your position is a little worse and your clock is running down, this is a very unpleasant situation to face as it is easy to go wrong and pick the line that turns out to be inferior. } (25. Ne5 Bd6) 25... gxf4 { Karjakin chooses the best continuation. Playing 25...g4 instead would have led to an eventual opening up of the h-file (after the insertion of h2-h3 & h7-h5 eventually) and this would likely be more dangerous than the opening up of the g-file as in the game, since the g-file is better controlled. Also, if Black had gone 25...g4 then eventually the K-side structure would have been g3+f4 for White and f5+g4 for Black. The f5-pawn could then be attacked by the White R+N quite easily (e.g. N on e3, R on h5) and losing that pawn would cost the game as the g4 pawn would fall shortly afterwards. } 26. gxf4 b5! { With this move, black is potentially making use of the 'a' file. } 27. axb5 axb5 { [%csl Gc4,Gf8][%cal Gg1g8,Ga8a1,Gd8a8,Ga8a2,Ge1g1,Gg1g5,Gg5g8,Ge8e1] } 28. Ne3 c6 { The position has now three shared files. The excitement and tension is starting to increase quite dramatically and unexpectedly. Black has possibilities of Ra8-a2, but in return White might have possibilities of Kf3 Rg1-g5. } 29. Kf3 { This provides now White the opportunity of Rg1-g5. Black needs to start treading carefully here. } 29... Ra8 { The rook is very keen to start using the 'a' file. } 30. Rg1 { White is now threatening Rg5. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf8h6] } (30. b3!? { right away is also interesting, with similar ideas to the game, e.g. } 30... Ra2 31. Rg1! $36) 30... Ra2?! { Just when it seemed black should be fine with just Bh6 to defend against Rg5, the position now takes an even more dramatic turn. } { Karjakin gets overzealous and tries to 'force' a draw a little too early, through active play. Instead, the position called for passive defense for a few more moves. As a consequence of this and Sergei's next move, Carlsen now gets a real chance to press for victory. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gg1g8] } (30... Bh6! { This seems sufficient enough to parry any of White's threats like Rg5. } 31. Rg3 Ra4 32. Rh3 Kg6 33. b3 Rxd4 (33... Rb4 { This is the computer's suggested line, but it's very unhuman to place your rook on b4, so I imagine Karjakin would have discarded the line after seeing that he could not capture on d4 immediately (in the event that he analyzed this line to begin with). }) 34. Rxh6+! { is the clever point! } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gg6h6,Re3f5] }) (30... h6?! 31. h4 { With the idea of h5 - black could start to be in real trouble here. } 31... Ra2 32. b3 c5! { This would essentially help activate the rook on a2 even further because it aims to cause maximum disruption for the rook to be able to invade later to h2. } 33. h5?! { Although seemingly an attractive idea is Rg6, black is able to equalise here. } (33. d5 c4 34. h5 cxb3 35. cxb3 Rh2 { Black has the advantage here. }) (33. Rg8! Kf7 34. Rg2 cxd4 35. Nxf5 d3 36. cxd3 Ra3 37. Rb2 $14 { White has an advantage here. }) 33... cxd4 34. Rg6+ Kf7 35. Nxf5 Rxc2 36. Nxd4 Rh2 37. Kg4 Rg2+ { And black is fine here. } 38. Kf5 Rh2 { The h pawn can be a liability } 39. Rf6+ Kg7 40. Rg6+ $10 { White would have nothing better than repetition checks here. }) (30... Ra4 { can be met with } 31. Rg5 Rxd4 32. Rxf5+ { when } 32... Kg7? { runs into } 33. Rxb5! $16) 31. b3 c5!? { The audience now should wake up! Going from one shared file to 3 with the rooks doing their own thing and the knight vs bishop imbalance, is starting to make this game border on "exciting" status. } 32. Rg8! { Neither d5 or dxc5 seem to offer white any real prospects for an advantage. } (32. dxc5 Bxc5 { This would simply activate blacks bishop and the pin is quite uncomfortable for White here. } 33. Rg2 Bxe3 34. Kxe3 $10 { This is very drawish indeed. }) (32. d5 h6 { To parry Rg5. Black would now threaten not jut c4 potentially but the subtle Ra3 for c4 as well. } 33. Rg8 Kf7 34. Rg2 Ra3 { With the threat of c4 } 35. Nxf5 c4 36. Nd4 cxb3 37. Nxb3 Ra4 $10 { Black seems fine here. The position is about equal. Black has succeeded in activating his bishop - at the relatively small cost of an extra pawn island. }) 32... Kf7 { In attacking the rook, the f5 pawn is neglected } 33. Rg2! { White has essentially said - "I will swap you my d4 pawn for your f5 pawn". } { This clever idea of first playing 32.Rg8 and only after forcing 32...Kf7 does White drop the rook back to g2 is what Karjakin missed. The point is that now White is prepared to meet cxd4 with the move Nxf5, after which White will pick off the d4 pawn sooner or later and emerge a pawn up. } 33... cxd4 (33... Kf6?! 34. dxc5 Bxc5 { The key difference here from the more immediate dxc5 is that this is no longer an awkard pin. White has also a great tactic here as well. } 35. Nxf5! Kxf5 36. Rg5+ Kf6 37. Rxc5 $16 { This is a very promising position for White to win. }) 34. Nxf5 d3! { Black is sacrificing a pawn to try and wreck White's pawn strucuture. } { The best practical try. The pawn was lost regardless, but this way at least all of White's pawns are isolated and it makes any attempts to convert the position particularly tough. } (34... Bc5 35. Ke4 $16 { This is much better for White. }) 35. cxd3 { The first time in the game, that someone is material up. White is a pawn up but black has active pieces and White has essentially 4 pawn islands. } 35... Ra1 { With the idea of Rb1. } 36. Nd4 b4 { Fixing the b3 pawn } 37. Rg5 { A flexible move introducing Rb5 Rd5 and Rh5 possibilities. } 37... Rb1 (37... Bg7!? { This seems an interesting alternative to Rb1 } 38. Rd5 Ke8 39. Nc2 Rf1+ 40. Ke4 Bc3 41. Rh5 { This sort of position carries some risk of White loses the b3 pawn under the wrong circumstances. }) 38. Rf5+ Ke8 39. Rb5 Rf1+ 40. Ke4 { The King infiltration is dangerous. White seems to have got a very real advantage now. } 40... Re1+ 41. Kf5 { Going away from black's checks. } 41... Rd1 42. Re5+ (42. Rb8+!? Ke7 43. Ke4 Re1+ 44. Kd5 { This position seems very dangerous for black but difficult to prove concretely how White can actually win. }) 42... Kf7 43. Rd5 { Offering d3 for d7 } 43... Rxd3 44. Rxd7+ Ke8 45. Rd5 Rh3 46. Re5+ Kf7 47. Re2 { White seems to have made some progress. With less pawn islands to worry about and an aggressive King it seems as though this is the ideal starting "torture" position for Magnus to have. } 47... Bg7 48. Nc6 { Nd8 is a very important threat here. } 48... Rh5+ 49. Kg4 Rc5 50. Nd8+ Kg6 51. Ne6 h5+ 52. Kf3 Rc3+ 53. Ke4 { White now threatens to end the game with Rg2+ } 53... Bf6 54. Re3 h4 55. h3 { Putting pawns on light squares seems entirely logical - safely away from black's dark squared bishop. } 55... Rc1 56. Nf8+ Kf7 57. Nd7 Ke6 58. Nb6 Rd1 59. f5+ Kf7 60. Nc4 Rd4+ 61. Kf3 Bg5?! { It seems the game has some extra twists and turns to it. Rd5 seemed a more direct way of playing to equalise. } (61... Rd5!? { This seems to offer black a safe way of equalising } 62. Kf4 Rd4+ 63. Re4 Rd3 64. Re3 Rd4+ 65. Kf3 Rd5 66. Kg4 Rd4+ 67. Kh5 Rd5 68. Rf3 Rd8 $10 { Black seems to be holding here }) 62. Re4 Rd3+ 63. Kg4 Rg3+ 64. Kh5 Be7 65. Ne5+ Kf6 66. Ng4+ Kf7 67. Re6 { With this move, it looks as though White has built up a decisive advantage. One key threat is now Ne5+ with mating net implications. } 67... Rxh3 (67... Rxb3?! 68. Ne5+ Kg7 69. Rxe7+ Kf6 70. Nc6 Rb1 71. Kg4 Rg1+ 72. Kxh4 Kxf5 73. Rb7 $18 { White is winning here }) 68. Ne5+ Kg7 { The most tenacious way to fight on. Black offers a piece sac trying to transpose into potentially drawing positions. } 69. Rxe7+ Kf6 70. Nc6 Kxf5 { Here is the golden moment of truth. It seems almost like a composition position now - and not from a real game. White has one move which is essentially decisive. In this modern era, all spectators on their smart phones let alone desktops can find this move instantly. } 71. Na5 { [%csl Ga5] } (71. Re1!! { This would be an absolutely brilliant move. But the players have been playing for about 5 hours now, and apparently Magnus is human after all. } 71... Kf4 (71... Rxb3?? 72. Nd4+ Kf4 73. Nxb3) (71... Rc3 72. Ne7+! { A killer check! } 72... Kf4 (72... Kf6 73. Nd5+ $18 { Winning the rook as well }) 73. Nd5+ { Ouch! } 73... Kf3 74. Nxc3 bxc3 75. Kxh4 { And White wins }) (71... Rd3 72. Kxh4 Kf6 73. Na5 $18 { White is winning technically here. }) (71... Rh2 72. Nxb4 Rd2 73. Rf1+ Ke5 74. Rf3 Ke4 75. Rc3 Kf5 76. Nc6 $18 { White is winning technically }) 72. Rf1+ Ke4 (72... Ke3? 73. Kg4 Rh2 74. Nxb4 h3 75. Rc1 { Cutting the black king off } 75... Ke4 76. Rc4+ Ke5 77. Nd3+ Kd6 78. Rc3 Rh1 79. Nf2 Rg1+ 80. Kxh3 $18) 73. Na5 Kd4 74. Kg4 Rc3 75. Kxh4 { This position can be won } 75... Kd3 76. Rf4 Rc5 77. Nc4 Kc2 78. Rf3 Rc8 79. Kg3 Re8 { White still has work to do, but the position is technically winnable. }) (71. Re8) 71... Rh1 { Black has a dangerous asset here - the h pawn. This makes the win for White highly problematic in practice - if there is indeed a win. } 72. Rb7? { It seems that black's a pawn is getting very dangerous now and can provide black with huge drawing opportunities. } (72. Rf7+! { This might represent the correct winning procedure. } 72... Ke6 73. Rf2 h3 74. Kh4 h2 75. Ra2 Ke5 76. Kg3 Rc1 77. Rxh2 Rc3+ 78. Kg4 Kd4 79. Kf4 $18) 72... Ra1!! { This deserves two exclamation marks. It is a highly precise move played under severe time pressure. Karjakin his displaying his fantastic traits at the candidates tournament - highlight resilient and incredibly resourceful. Very accurate under time pressure. Gaining a key tempo on the knight, and the h pawn is trying to run down the board. } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Ga1a5,Gh4h1,Gf5f4,Gf4g2] } 73. Rb5+ { Technically the position is drawing now. } (73. Nc4!? { Although interesting, it seems black is able to draw here with the right procedure. See example variation. Black can give up the h pawn and aim for a very awkwardly placed knight on a4 where Rxb3 becomes possible because the White king is too far away from black's b pawn. } 73... h3 74. Rf7+ Ke6 75. Rf2 Rh1 76. Rb2 h2 77. Kh4 Kd5 78. Nb6+ Kc5 79. Na4+ Kb5 80. Kg3 Rd1 81. Kxh2 Rd3 82. Kg2 Rxb3 { Draws by force } 83. Rxb3 Kxa4 84. Rb1 Ka3 85. Ra1+ Kb2 86. Ra6 b3 87. Kf1 Kc2 88. Rc6+ Kd1 89. Rb6 Kc2 $10) 73... Kf4 74. Rxb4+ Kg3 { The black h pawn secures the draw here } 75. Rg4+ Kf2 { [%csl Gh4][%cal Ga1a5] } 76. Nc4 (76. Rxh4 Rxa5+ 77. Kg4 Ke3 $10) 76... h3 77. Rh4 (77. Ne5 h2 78. Nd3+ Kf3 79. Ne5+ Ke3 80. Nc4+ Kf2 81. Rh4 h1=Q 82. Rxh1 Rxh1+ 83. Kg5 Ke2 { If anyone is better it is black here. }) 77... Kg3 78. Rg4+ { White has nothing better than this. In fact White can end up losing the position if he tries too hard. } (78. Ne3?? Ra5+ 79. Kg6 Kxh4 $19 { And black wins }) (78. Ne5 h2?? 79. Ng4 Ra5+ $19) 78... Kf2 { This game shows remarkable defensive resourcefulness of Karjakin. If there is one player in the world who is able to defend with the accuracy needed and ingenuity it is Sergey Karjakin as this game shows. By far the most interesting game of the match to analyse so far, and a treat for the spectators as the game unfolded from apparently a drawish looking opening position. The World championship has ignited with interest now! } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "0:34:33-0:04:33"]
[Date "2016.11.15"]
