[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 { Sergey continues with 1.e4 as he did before with the White pieces. Annotations by Kingscrusher. Video at : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O0Hdp7mNY_M } 1... e5 { Magnus again responds classically. } 2. Nf3 { Attacking the e5 pawn } 2... Nc6 { Defending the e5 pawn } 3. Bb5 { The classic Ruy Lopez } 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 { The same moves as Game 2 so far. Re1 is actually the most popular move here. } 6. Re1 { A novelty from Game 2 where d3 was played. Re1 is actually the most popular move here. } 6... b5 { The standard move } 7. Bb3 O-O { Both sides are now safely castled } 8. h3 { c3 is also popular here } 8... Bb7 { This is the main move here } 9. d3 { This is the main move with one idea of blunting the b7 bishop } 9... d6 { Now that the e5 pawn has extra protection, the Knight on c6 threatens Na5 } 10. a3 { To give the bishop a square in the event of Na5 } 10... Qd7 { The 2nd most popular move here. More usual is Na5. } 11. Nbd2 { The Knight often heads for f1 where it can go either to e3 or g3 } 11... Rfe8 { This rook move facilitates Bf8 which will further support the e5 pawn and in turn possibly facilitate d5 later. } 12. c3 { A little bit of a suprise from a theoretical perspective. More usual is Nf1. } 12... Bf8 13. Nf1 h6 { This move prevents Bg5 from White which can be annoying. } 14. N3h2 { [%csl Bh6,Gf6][%cal Bd1f3,Yc1h6] } 14... d5 { This is a common liberating move. Here it seems more tempting than before h6 is played. } 15. Qf3 { White wants to keep the b7 bishop blunted, so just protects the e4 pawn. exd5 instead would perhaps liberate black's pieces too much. With this move White also threatens Bxh6 because the Knight on f6 can be taken after gxf6. } { [%cal Bd5e4,Yb7e4] } (15. exd5?! Nxd5 16. Bc2 a5 { Black would be very active here. }) 15... Na5 { Attacking the b3 bishop and opening up the b7 bishop to put pressure on the e4 pawn. After this counter threat, White's initial threat of Bxh6 may need to be addressed. } 16. Ba2 { Keeping the bishop on the more black King sensitive diagonal. The threat of Bxh6 has been renewed. } (16. Bc2?! { This seems a bit passive } 16... Qe6) 16... dxe4 { Resolving the central pawn tension } 17. dxe4 { Again the initial threat of Bxh6 has been renewed } 17... Nc4 { With this move Magnus is actually ignoring the threat now of Bxh6 } 18. Bxh6 { Wins a pawn but black has a certain pressure compensation on e4 } { [%cal Gg7h6,Gf3f6] } 18... Qc6! { Protecting the f6 knight and putting more pressure on e4. The threat now is gxh6. Black is actually winning his pawn back here. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gf1g3,Gg7h6] } (18... gxh6? 19. Qxf6 { This is just really bad for black } 19... Nxb2 20. Qg6+ Bg7 21. Ng4 Re6 22. Bxe6 Qxe6 23. Nxh6+ Kf8 24. Qxe6 fxe6 25. Ng4 $19 { And black is winning }) (18... Nxe4? { This may have been the seemingly brilliant line that Sergey had in mind when he played Bxh6. Unfortunately for Sergey, Qc6 is far more effective and simple. } 19. Rxe4 f5? { This would allow a brilliant Queen sac } (19... Bxe4 20. Qxe4 gxh6 21. Ne3 { White has a nice position here }) 20. Rxc4 Bxf3 (20... bxc4 21. Qxb7 $18 { White is clearly winning here }) 21. Rxc7+ Bd5 22. Rxd7 Bxa2 23. Rxa2 { And White is winning }) 19. Bxc4?! { Many commentators around the World believe this move was not the best as it voluntarily gives up a potentially useful bishop and gives black a bind on light squares as well. Perhaps Sergey at this point in the game was annoyed because of missing Qc6 and having a slightly worse position. It is interesting that even Super-GMs can make their position unnecessarily even worse when annoyed - so they are human like us bunnies after all :) } (19. Bc1!? { This might be an interesting alternative which defends b2 } 19... Nxe4 20. Ne3 Ned6 21. Qxc6 Bxc6 22. Nxc4 Nxc4 { Black has fully equalised here }) 19... bxc4 { Magnus does not mind doubled pawns here } 20. Be3 Nxe4 { It seems black has more than equalised. Magnus has essentially gained an important center pawn for the h6 flank pawn. Whilst it can be argued that the h6 pawn is part of black's king safety, one also has to note that the attacking light squared bishop is no longer on the board. So overall it seems Magnus has done very well out of the opening here and even has a slight advantage. } 21. Ng3 Nd6 { Offering the trade of queens } 22. Rad1 Rab8 { Black is looking forward to pressurising the backward b2 pawn } 23. Bc1 f6 { Black's bishop pair and b file pressure more than compensate for the doubled c pawns. } 24. Qxc6 Bxc6 25. Ng4 Rb5 { By supporting e5 with this rook move, black may even consider f5 } 26. f3 f5 { Pushing the knight back. White seems passive } 27. Nf2 Be7 28. f4 Bh4! { An interesting sharp alternative to e4 or exf4 } (28... exf4!? { This seems a plausible alternative } 29. Ne2 Bf6 30. Nd4 Rxe1+ 31. Rxe1 Bxd4 32. cxd4 f3 33. g4 Ne4 34. Nxe4 fxe4 35. h4 Rb3 36. Re3 { Possibly White has enough of a fortress here to hold especially with the opposite coloured bishops. }) (28... e4?! { Although attractive in one sense of apparently having a protected passed pawn, White can effectively blockade on e3 here. } 29. Nf1 { The e3 blockade square seems attractive here } 29... g6 30. Ne3 Bh4 31. Re2 { White seems safe enough here in this blockading scenario. }) 29. fxe5 { Virtually forced } (29. Nf1? Ne4 { White would be losing material here }) (29. Kh2? exf4 30. Bxf4 { Losing protection of b2 } 30... Rxe1 31. Rxe1 Rxb2 { Black is winning here. This bishop needs to be protecting b2 }) 29... Bxg3 30. exd6 Rxe1+ 31. Rxe1 cxd6 { The question is if black has enough advantage here to convert to a win. } 32. Rd1 Kf7 33. Rd4 Re5 34. Kf1 { The threat of Re1+ had to be parried. } (34. Rxc4?? Re1# { Is a mate in 1 }) 34... Rd5 35. Rxd5 (35. Rxc4?? Bb5 { Is a winning pin }) 35... Bxd5 { The starting position for a Magnus torture session. } 36. Bg5 Kg6 { [%csl Gd8,Ge3][%cal Gg5e3] } 37. h4 { It seems strange to play this instead of Bd8. The h4 pawn is now a target of Kh5. The point is to try and give the knight some active squares in particular the h3 square. } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gh3h4,Gf2h3] } (37. Bd8 { This seems a plausible option if White didn't want to commit to h4 }) (37. Be3!? { This is another viable alternative } 37... Kh5 38. Bb6 { White has a solid enough position to perhaps secure a draw here }) 37... Kh5 38. Nh3 Bf7 (38... Bxh4!? 39. Nf4+ Kg4! { Slightly stronger than Kxg5 } 40. Bxh4 Kxf4 { The opposite coloured bishops offer White good drawing chances } 41. Kf2 Ke4 42. Be7 Kd3 43. Bxd6 Kc2 44. Be5 Kxb2 45. a4 a5 46. Ke3 Kb3 47. g3 Kxa4 48. Bc7 { This is an example scenario where the opposite coloured bishops can help White achieve a draw. }) 39. Be7 Bxh4 40. Bxd6 Bd8 41. Ke2 g5 { Magnus has a 2 to 1 pawn majority on the K-side. White Queens side majority is currently nullified by the restraining c4 pawn which is supported nicely by the bishop on f7. The other aspect here is that White has weakened light squares on the queenside where the black king may want to try and invade into later. The torture scene has been set for a long tortuous grind based on these aspects. } 42. Nf2 { [%csl Gf5,Gg5,Gg2,Gb3,Gc2,Gb1][%cal Gh5a2] } 42... Kg6 43. g4 { Trying to set up a firm blockade against Black's pawn majority on the K-side. } 43... Bb6 (43... f4!? { This seems a plausible alternative } 44. Bc5 Be6 45. Kf3 { Possibly it is this kind of position which seems to blockade black's pawns which put Magnus off this option of playing f4. }) 44. Be5 a5 45. Nd1 f4 (45... Be6!? { A viable alternative to the comital f4. This alternative plan of just having the g pawn may not be enough though. } 46. gxf5+ Kxf5 47. Bg3 Kg4 48. Be5 Kh3 49. Kf1 g4 50. Nf2+ Kh4 51. Ne4 { White can set up a blockade on g3 here } 51... Bd5 52. Ng3 { It is difficult to see how black breaks through here. }) 46. Bd4 Bc7 47. Nf2 Be6 48. Kf3 Bd5+ 49. Ke2 Bg2 50. Kd2 Kf7 51. Kc2 Bd5 52. Kd2 Bd8 53. Kc2 Ke6 { The King heads towards the Queenside } 54. Kd2 Kd7 55. Kc2 Kc6 56. Kd2 Kb5 57. Kc1 Ka4 58. Kc2 Bf7 59. Kc1 Bg6 60. Kd2 Kb3 61. Kc1 Bd3 62. Nh3 Ka2 63. Bc5 Be2 64. Nf2 Bf3 65. Kc2 Bc6 66. Bd4 Bd7 67. Bc5 Bc7 68. Bd4 Be6 69. Bc5 f3 70. Be3 Bd7 { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gc7b6,Gb6f2] } 71. Kc1! { It is important not to take on g5 which would allow Bb6. White is firmly keeping his blockade on the black pawns. } (71. Bxg5?? Bb6 { This is winning for black } 72. Ne4 Bxg4 73. Kc1 f2 74. Nd2 Bh3 75. Bh4 f1=Q+ 76. Nxf1 Bxf1 $19 { And black is winning }) 71... Bc8 72. Kc2 Bd7 73. Kc1 Bf4 74. Bxf4 gxf4 75. Kc2 Be6 76. Kc1 Bc8 77. Kc2 Be6 78. Kc1 Kb3 79. Kb1 Ka4 80. Kc2 Kb5 81. Kd2 Kc6 82. Ke1 Kd5 83. Kf1 Ke5 84. Kg1 Kf6 { Black threatens Kg5 now } 85. Ne4+ Kg6 86. Kf2 Bxg4 87. Nd2 Be6 88. Kxf3 Kf5 89. a4 Bd5+ 90. Kf2 Kg4 91. Nf1 Kg5 92. Nd2 Kf5 93. Ke2 Kg4 94. Kf2 { Draw agreed. There are no real winning chances for either side in this heavily simplified position. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
