[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 { Sergey again sticks with 1.e4 - Annotations by Kingscrusher. Video at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2wtY05aIybQ&t=955s } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The classical Ruy Lopez } 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O { This is quite an important nuance because it means that black could consider the respectable Marshall Gambit now if White plays c3. The more common move is d6 which indicates White is not going to play the Marshall Gambit. } 8. h3 { This is an anti-marshall gambit variation, but a very common move. } (8. c3 d5 { The Marshall Gambit - super GMs like Michael Adams often play this and often use it as a drawing tool with the black pieces against other Super-GMs. }) 8... Bb7 9. d3 d5 { Very energetic. More often played is d6. With this move, Magnus indicates he wants to have a potentially more aggressive game. It implies a pawn sac on e5 - making this system a kind of gambit relation of the Marshall Gambit where black offers the e5 pawn. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxe5 Nd4 { For the gambit pawn, Black has great piece play, and is able to also take out White's b3 bishop. Of course it does not look like Black is doing some sort of Marshall Gambit hack-attack here - instead there are certain positional trump cards Black is trying to evolve from here, such as the b7 bishop activity, and the potential to double White's queenside pawns. With Nd4 Black does not have to be concerned too much about a4, as is often the case in other variations of the standard Ruy Lopez. } (11... Nxe5!? { This is a popular alternative which has seen some great wins for black } 12. Rxe5 Qd6 13. Re1 Rae8 14. Nd2 c5 15. Ne4 Qc6 16. a4 { There have been at least three interesting wins for black here from this position - Van Kampen vs Hebden 2012, Abdumalik vs Sachdev 2014, and Craig Sadler vs Roman Nizky 2012 } 16... Nb6 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qf3 c4 19. Ba2 f5 { This follows a stem game Abdumalik vs Sachdev 0-1 in 2014 }) 12. Nc3 Nb4 { The most common move here but there are not too many stem games from this particular position. } 13. Bf4 { Ne4 has been played more here } (13. a3!? { Some may find it tempting to kick the knight on b4 but it leads to a level position } 13... Nxb3 14. cxb3 f6 15. Ng4 Nc6) 13... Nxb3 14. axb3 c5 { Black keeps a firm grip on the d4 square. } 15. Ne4 f6 { Magnus is still in his preparation because apparently he was playing this move very quickly. } (15... f5!? 16. Ng3 Bd6) 16. Nf3 f5 { This seems a plausible alternative } 17. Neg5 (17. Ned2!? $10 { This is a solid alternative } 17... Bf6 $10 { The position is equal here technically }) (17. Ng3? { This would be a terrible move here } 17... Bxf3! { The Knight on b4 has annoying pressure on c2 which is emphasised here } 18. Qxf3 (18. gxf3 Bf6 $15 { This would be pretty wretched pawn structure for White. } 19. Qc1 Qd5 20. Kg2 h6 21. Nh5 $15 { Technically better for black although not entirely losing for White. }) 18... Nxc2 $19 { And black wins material here }) 17... Bxg5 18. Nxg5 (18. Bxg5? { This would be a mistake } 18... Bxf3 19. Qc1 (19. Bxd8? Bxd1 20. Be7 Bxc2 $19) 19... Qd5 20. gxf3 Qxf3 21. Re3 Qh5 22. Bf4 (22. Rg3 f4 23. Bxf4 Nxc2 $17 24. Qxc2 Rxf4) 22... Rae8 23. c3 Rxe3 24. Qxe3 Qg6+ 25. Qg3 Nxd3 $17) 18... h6 { Not fearing Ne6 because black has Qd5 if needed } 19. Ne6 Qd5 { Threatening Qxg2 mate } 20. f3 { Not just parrying mate, but also blunting the b7 bishop. It is of course at the cost of some extra dark square weaknesses. } 20... Rfe8 21. Re5 (21. Nc7!? { This seems possible even though it seems to allow Qd4+ and QxB } 21... Qd4+ 22. Kh1 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Qxf4 24. Nxa8 Nxc2 25. Qe7 Nxa1 (25... Bxa8 26. Rxa6 Qc1+ 27. Kh2 Qf4+ $10) 26. Qxb7 Qg5 27. Nc7 $10) (21. Qe2? { This loses in at least two ways - Kf7 or Bc8 } 21... Kf7! { Black gets the e6 knight here with this carnivorous king move! } (21... Bc8! 22. Nc7 Rxe2 23. Nxd5 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Nxd5)) 21... Qd6 22. c3 (22. Qe2!? { This seems a plausible alternative here to support the e6 knight } 22... Rxe6 23. Rxe6 Qxf4 24. c3 Nd5 25. c4 Nb4 26. cxb5 Qd4+ 27. Kh2 Bd5 28. Re7 $10 { Technically an equal position. Dynamically balanced. }) 22... Rxe6 (22... Nxd3?! 23. Rxc5 Qxe6 24. Qxd3 Qxb3 25. Qd7 Qf7 26. Qxf7+ Kxf7 27. Rxf5+ Kg6 28. Rc5 $16 { Although White is better here and a pawn up, the likelihood of a draw is high because of the opposite coloured bishops. }) 23. Rxe6 Qxe6 24. cxb4 cxb4 25. Rc1 { The position technically is level here. Ideally if White was given some moves, then d4, Be5, and Rc7 would be the dream position to attack from. However Magnus is immediately contesting the c-file now with his next move. } 25... Rc8 26. Rxc8+ { Futher simplifcation - } 26... Qxc8 27. Qe1 { Hitting the b4 pawn but also it carries the idea of attacking with Qe7 and Be5. Winning prospects for both sides are severely limited now in this simplified position. But black needs to be careful about Queen invasions. } 27... Qd7 { This is a very solid move because it rules out Qe7 from White and also hits d3. } 28. Kh2 { Instead of taking on b4, this move offers black the option of Qxd3 to which White might actually go into an attack mode instead of taking on b4 with the move Qe8+ and Be5 } (28. Qxb4!? Qxd3 29. Bg3 $10) 28... a5! { This move errs on the side of caution, protecting the b4 pawn instead of taking on d3. By not taking on d3, the back row is not neglected to a possible Qe8+. } (28... Qxd3 29. Qe8+! { This may be a way of saccing a pawn to try and get some sort of coordinated attack. } (29. Qe7 { Not as strong as Qe8+ } 29... Qd5 30. Be5 Qf7 31. Qxb4 Bd5 32. Qd6 Bxb3 33. Qxa6 Bc4 34. b3 Bxb3 35. Qxb5 $10) 29... Kh7 30. Be5 { Black would need to be very careful here. } 30... Qd5?? (30... f4! { This may hold for black now. } 31. Qf7 (31. Bxf4 Qc2 { Black threatens Bxf3 here } 32. Qe3 Bd5 33. Be5 Bxb3 34. Qa7 Qg6 $10) 31... Qg6 32. Qxb7 Qg3+ 33. Kg1 Qe1+ $10 { With perpetual check }) 31. Qe7 Qg8 32. Qxb7 $18) 29. Qe3 Bd5 { b3 is a weak pawn but in return White can hit a5 } 30. Qb6 { Hitting a5 in return } 30... Bxb3 31. Qxa5 Qxd3 32. Qxb4 Be6 { Draw agreed. If White tries Be5 with the idea of Qe7, black can reply safely with Qd7 to stop any further pressure on his king and still hold the b5 pawn as well. Black is solid enough here in this simplified position. } 1/2-1/2


