[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "0:21:33-1:04:33"]
[Date "2016.11.20"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D10"]
[Opening "Slav Defense"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 7 - 20th Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/BOHrDIHi"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. d4 { Sergey varies with 1.d4. Statistically Sergey has played 1.e4 throughout his career more than 10 times as much as 1.d4 } 1... d5 { A classical reply echoing the reduction of imbalances from the black perspective over wanting dynamic play. In a World championship match with the black pieces, the key thing is usually to avoid losing. } 2. c4 c6 { The Slav defence - which some consider a kind of "upgrade" to the more classical Queens Gambit Declined because the c8 bishop is not hemmed in. } 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 { The second most popular move here to playing e6. Black deprives White of the b5 square in some variations. Additionally a quirky feature of this move is that sometimes Ra7 is handy to protect b7. } 5. Bd3 { More often played is Nf3 or Qc2 } 5... dxc4 { Whilst b5 is a more popular move, statistically the win % for White when b5 played is significantly higher than when dxc4 is played. This may be a testament to dxc4 being more "solid". } 6. Bxc4 e6 { Magnus again rejects b5 which is actually the more popular move here generally in practice. } 7. Nf3 c5 { With this move, the c8 bishop issue is partially addressed because if black gets in b5, then Bb7 is a nice logical diagonal for the c8 bishop. } 8. O-O b5 { Giving the b7 square for the c8 bishop } 9. Be2 Bb7 10. dxc5 { This is the most often played move here. It avoids the possibility of being saddled with an isolated queen pawn. But it does mean now there is a symmetrical pawn structure. } 10... Nc6 { This is the first big theoretical departure. Most often Bxc5 or Qxd1 is played. There does not seem anything available to punish this move in any way however, and black is making sure b4 is not possible to support the c5 pawn. One high level game with this move is Alexey Tomilin vs Ponomariov (a former FIDE WOrld champion) played in 2006 which ended in black winning. } 11. Nd2 { The game now goes off the beaten track. a3 and Qc2 have been tried before. } 11... Bxc5 12. Nde4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Be7 14. b3 Nb4 { Threatening Bxe4 } 15. Bf3 O-O 16. Ba3 Rc8!? { Technically a "mistake" but perhaps not such a great issue. More solid would have been Bd5 } (16... Bd5 { Black would be very solid here, and perhaps even consider a move like Qa5 soon. }) 17. Nf6+ { This move guarantees White a small technical advantage. } 17... Bxf6 18. Bxb7 Bxa1 19. Bxb4 Bf6!? { This leaves black a pawn down } (19... Rc7!? { This may be the safest move technically } 20. Bf3? (20. Qf3 Qd7 21. Bxf8 Rxb7 22. Rxa1 Kxf8 $10 { The position is about equal here }) (20. Bxa6 Qxd1 21. Rxd1 Rb8 { An interesting variation Where black traps the a6 bishop. } 22. Rxa1 Rc6 23. Bxb5 Rxb5 24. Bd2 Ra6 25. Rc1 Rb8 26. Rc2 $15 { Black is slightly better here }) 20... Qxd1 21. Rxd1 Rfc8 { And black is winning here }) 20. Bxf8 Qxd1 (20... Qxf8? 21. Bxc8 Qxc8 { And White is winning - the exchange up }) 21. Rxd1 Rxf8 22. Bxa6 { Although White is a pawn up here, it is an opposite coloured bishop scenario which often helps secure a draw. } 22... b4 { Locking down White's Queenside pawns. } 23. Rc1 g6! { A mistake would be Bc3 because then a4! } (23... Bc3 24. a4! { Here white has an outside passed pawn, and black's defensive task would be much more difficult. }) 24. Rc2 Ra8 25. Bd3 Rd8 26. Be2 Kf8 27. Kf1 Ra8 28. Bc4 Rc8 29. Ke2 Ke7 30. f4 h6 31. Kf3 Rc7 32. g4 g5 33. Ke4 Rc8 { Draw agreed. White does not have an "exploitable advantage". The extra pawn is nullified as long as black doesn't play a move like Bc3 which would allow a4 with a passed pawn. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "0:14:33-0:31:33"]
