[ChapterName "Game 9 - 23rd Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/E1ZujQDY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 { Sergey uses his most practiced move. He has played 1.e4 more than 10 times as much as 1.d4 in his chess career. Analysis by Kingscrusher. Video at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LH6LwtX8Lf4 } 1... e5 { Magnus replies classically. Some expected a Sicilian defence or other system given that a win has become very important now because of the match situation. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 { Varying from the usual Be7 } 6. Bb3 Bc5 7. a4 Rb8 8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. axb5 axb5 11. Na3 O-O { A well know pawn sac idea } 12. Nxb5 Bg4 13. Bc2 exd4 14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Bxf3 16. gxf3 (16. Qxf3 Bxd4 $15 { Black has more than equalised here }) 16... Nh5 17. Kh1 Qf6 18. Be3 c5 { Ra8 has been tried a bit before as well } 19. e5 Qe6 (19... dxe5? 20. dxc5 Rfd8 21. Qe2 Bc7 22. Ra6 Qe7 23. Ra7 $16 { White is doing very nicely here }) 20. exd6 c4 (20... cxd4 21. Bxd4 Rfd8 22. Re1 Qxd6 $14) 21. b3 cxb3 (21... c3 22. d5 Qxd6 23. Qd3 { Threatening Qxh7+ } 23... g6 24. Ra6 $14) 22. Bxb3 Qxd6 23. Ra6 Rfd8 24. Rg1 Qd7 { By unpinning the b6 bishop, now Bxd4 is threatened } (24... Nf4?! { Although tempting Qc2 is strong threatening Bxf7+ and Qf5+ } 25. Qc2! Ng6 26. Qf5 Qc7 27. Ba2 $16) 25. Rg4 { Protecting d4 pawn } 25... Nf6 26. Rh4 Qb5 (26... Qb7 27. Ra1 Rd6 $14) 27. Ra1 g6 28. Rb1 { Threatening Bxf7+ winning the queen on b5 } 28... Qd7 29. Qd3 { Things are brewing here against g6. For example Rbg1 and Rxg6+ may become very dangerous. } 29... Nd5 { Black unpins the f7 pawn with this blockading move } 30. Rg1 Bc7 (30... Nxe3?? 31. Rxg6+ hxg6 32. Qxg6+ Kf8 33. Qf6! { Forcing a mate in 2 } 33... Qe7 (33... Ke8 34. Rh8#) 34. Rh8#) 31. Bg5 Re8 32. Qc4 Rb5 { Carefully defending the d5 knight. Other options are disastrous. } (32... Ne7?? 33. Qxf7+ Kh8 34. Qxh7#) (32... Nb6? 33. Qxf7+ Qxf7 34. Bxf7+ Kxf7 35. Rxh7+ Kg8 36. Rxc7 $18) 33. Qc2 { Threatening now Ba4 } 33... Ra8 34. Bc4 Rba5 (34... Nb4?? { Has a major tactical flaw! } 35. Qxg6+ hxg6 (35... Kf8 36. Be7+ Kxe7 (36... Ke8 37. Qxf7#) (36... Qxe7 37. Qg8#) 37. Qxf7+ Kd6 38. Rh6+ Qe6 39. Rxe6#) 36. Bf6 Rh5 37. Rxh5 Qh3 38. Rxh3 g5 39. Rh8#) 35. Bd2 Ra4 (35... Ra1 36. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 37. Kg2 Bd8 38. Qb2 Bxh4 (38... Ra8 39. Re4 $14) 39. Qxa1 $14) 36. Qd3 Ra1 37. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 38. Kg2 Ne7 { A delicate moment. f7 seems like a vulnerable soft spot to be exploited but finding the most effective way is tricky here. } (38... Nb4) 39. Bxf7+!? { Maybe technically stronger was Qb3 } (39. Qb3! Nf5 (39... Qf5? 40. Re4 Bd6 41. Qb7 Ra3 (41... g5 42. Rxe7 Bxe7 43. Qxe7 g4 44. Qe8+ Kg7 45. Qe5+ $18) 42. Rxe7? (42. Bf4 $18 Bxf4 43. Rxe7 { Crushing black } 43... Bd6 44. Bxf7+ Kg7 45. Be6+ $18) 42... Bxe7 43. Qxe7 Qxf3+ 44. Kg1 Ra1+ 45. Be1 Qg4+ 46. Kf1 Qh3+ 47. Kg1 $10) 40. Bxf7+ Qxf7? (40... Kg7 41. Rh3 Ra6 42. Qd3 Rb6 43. Bb3 h5 44. d5 Be5 45. f4 Bf6 46. Bc3 $16) 41. Qxf7+ Kxf7 42. Rxh7+ Ng7 (42... Ke6 43. Rxc7 Nxd4 44. Rg7 Kf6? (44... Ra2 45. Bc3 Ne2 46. Rxg6+ Kf7 47. Rc6 Nf4+ 48. Kf1 $16) 45. Bc3 $18) 43. Bh6 $16 Bf4 44. Bxf4 Kg8 45. Rh6 Kf7 46. Be5 Nf5 47. Rh7+ Ke6 48. Rb7 $18 Ra5 49. Rb6+ Kd5 50. Rf6 Nxd4 51. Bxd4 Kxd4 52. Rxg6 $18) 39... Kxf7 40. Qc4+ Kg7 (40... Qe6?? 41. Rxh7+ Kf6 42. Qxc7 $18 Ra6 43. Qf4+ Qf5 44. Qh4+ Ke6 45. Qxe7+) 41. d5 { Threatening Qd4+ winning the rook on a1 } 41... Nf5 (41... g5!? 42. Bc3+ Kg6 43. Qd3+ Qf5 44. Re4 Ra4 45. d6 Rxe4 46. fxe4 Qg4+ 47. Kh1 Bd8 48. dxe7 Bxe7 $14) (41... Ra8?? { This greedy move would seal blacks fate because of the lethal battery White can quickly set up pointing at black's dark squares. } 42. Qd4+ Kg8 43. Bc3 { Threatening Qg7 mate } 43... Nxd5 44. Qh8+ Kf7 45. Qxh7+ Ke8 46. Qg8+ Ke7 47. Rh7+ Kd6 48. Rxd7+ $18) (41... Rd1 42. Bh6+ Kf6 (42... Kh8 43. Qc3+ Kg8 44. Qg7#) 43. Bg5+ Kg7 (43... Kxg5 44. Rxh7 Kf6 45. Qh4+ g5 46. Qh6+ Ke5 47. Qxg5+ Kd6 48. Qf6+ Kxd5 49. Rxe7 Qc8 50. Qf7+ Kd6 51. Rxc7) 44. d6 Bxd6 (44... Qxd6 45. Rxh7+ Kxh7 46. Qf7+ Kh8 47. Bf6+) 45. Rxh7+ Kxh7 46. Qf7+ Kh8 47. Bf6#) (41... Be5? 42. Bc3 Qf5 (42... Bxc3 43. Qxc3+ Kg8 44. Qxa1 $18) (42... Qd6 43. Qf4 Bxc3 44. Qxd6 $18) 43. Qc7 Bxc3 (43... Kf6 44. Qd6+ Kf7 45. Bxe5 Qg5+ 46. Rg4 Qh5 47. Rf4+ $18) 44. Qxc3+ Qf6 45. Rxh7+ Kxh7 46. Qxf6 $18) 42. Bc3+ (42. Re4? Rb1 $19) 42... Kf8 43. Bxa1 Nxh4+ 44. Qxh4 Qxd5 45. Qf6+ Qf7 (45... Ke8? 46. Qh8+ Kd7 47. Qxh7+ $18) 46. Qd4 { Although technically a pawn up, the doubled pawns do not help here. } 46... Ke8 47. Qe4+ Qe7 48. Qd5 Bd8 (48... h5? { As long as black doesn't go out of his way to lose another pawn, this position should be drawable for black. } 49. Qg8+ Kd7 50. Qxg6) 49. Kf1 Qf7 50. Qe4+ Qe7 51. Be5 Qe6 52. Kg2 Be7 53. Qa8+ Kf7 54. Qh8 h5 55. Qg7+ Ke8 56. Bf4 Qf7 57. Qh8+ Qf8 58. Qd4 Qf5 59. Qc4 Kd7 60. Bd2 Qe6 61. Qa4+ Qc6 62. Qa7+ Qc7 63. Qa2 Qd6 64. Be3 Qe6 65. Qa7+ Ke8 66. Bc5 Bd8 (66... Bxc5 67. Qxc5 Kf7 68. Kg3 $14) 67. h3 Qd5 68. Be3 Be7 69. Qb8+ Kf7 70. Qh8 Qe6 71. Bf4 Qf6 72. Qb8 Qe6 73. Qb7 Kg8 74. Qb5 Bf6 1/2-1/2


