[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "0:25:33-0:13:33"]
[Date "2016.11.17"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C54"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Classical Variation, Giuoco Pianissimo"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 5 - 17th Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/pHVQYIVs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { A deviation from the Ruy Lopez. The "Italian game". Annotations by Kingscrusher - video at: www.youtube.com/watch?v=xCcMvROwxVc&t=496s } { [%cal Yf1c4] } 3... Bc5 { The classic Giuoco Piano - Italian for "Quiet game". } { [%csl Bc5,Bc4] } 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 O-O 6. a4 { Quite a rare move here. More frequently played moves include: c3, Nbd2, Bb3, Re1 or Bg5 } 6... d6 7. c3 { Transposing into more normal lines } 7... a6 8. b4 Ba7 9. Re1 Ne7 10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. d4 c6 { [%cal Gc4b3] } 12. h3 (12. Bb3!? { This is an interesting alternative to stop the tactics with Nxe4 } 12... exd4 13. cxd4 $14 { White has a small edge here }) (12. Bd3) 12... exd4 13. cxd4 Nxe4 { A little tactic relying on d5 } 14. Bxf7+ (14. Nxe4!? d5 15. Bd3 dxe4 16. Bxe4 { White has an isolated Queens pawn here and black has a comfortable blockade with the immediate Be6 } 16... Be6 $10) 14... Rxf7 15. Nxe4 d5 { Preventing d5 from White, but inviting Nca5 } 16. Nc5 h6 { Prevening Ng5 } 17. Ra3 Bf5 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Qh4 { Indirectly preventing e6 because of the tactics on f2 } 20. Rf3 { Renewing the threat of e6 } (20. e6? Bxe6 21. Nxe6 (21. Rxe6 Qxf2+ 22. Kh1 Qf1+ 23. Qxf1 Rxf1+ 24. Kh2 Rxc1 $19 { Black is winning here }) 21... Bxf2+ 22. Kh2 Bxe1) 20... Bxc5 21. bxc5 Re8 { The scene is set. Black has a light square blockade. White can try and set up a dark square blockade in return. } 22. Rf4 Qe7 23. Qd4 { With opposite coloured bishops, the position here seems about equal right now. } 23... Ref8 24. Rf3 Be4 25. Rxf7 Qxf7 { Black has the annoying threat of Qg6 here } 26. f3 Bf5 27. Kh2 Be6 28. Re2 Qg6 29. Be3 Rf7 30. Rf2 Qb1 31. Rb2 Qf5 32. a5 { Locking down b7 and getting another pawn on a dark square away from Sergey's light squared bishop. } 32... Kf8 33. Qc3 Ke8 34. Rb4 g5 { Sergey is pursuing a kind of minority attack potentially with g4. But right now g4 is firmly under White's control. } 35. Rb2 Kd8 36. Rf2 Kc8 37. Qd4 Qg6 38. g4 { White potentially can play f4 now without having to be concerned about g4 from black. } (38. f4?! g4 39. hxg4 Qxg4 { Black is slightly better here }) 38... h5 39. Qd2 { This queen move has a slight downside in that black's d pawn could be potentially sacrificed with d4 now to try and liberate blacks bishop. } { [%csl Bg5][%cal Yd2g5,Yd5d4] } 39... Rg7 40. Kg3 Rg8 41. Kg2 hxg4 42. hxg4 d4 { A very interesting pawn to activate black's bishop on a great central square. } 43. Qxd4 Bd5 (43... Rh8! { This may be blacks best practical chance to try and win. However with the best defence, it should be possible for White to hold - so maybe Karjakin does not need to lose too much sleep over not playing this. } 44. Qe4 Qh6 { Threatening Qh3 and mating on h1 } 45. Kf1 Qh1+ 46. Ke2 Qa1!? (46... Rd8!? { Threatening Qd1 mate } 47. Rf1 { This seems safe enough for White } 47... Qg2+ (47... Qh4 48. Rf2 { White remains solid enough here }) 48. Rf2 Qg1 49. Rf1 { White can perpetually defend with RF2 and Rf1 here }) (46... Bd5!? 47. Qf5+ Kb8 48. Qd3! { To prevent Bc4+ } (48. e6?? Bc4+ 49. Kd2 Rd8+ 50. Kc3 Qe1+ 51. Kxc4 Qxe3 52. Qe4 (52. Rc2 Rd4#) 52... Qxf2 53. e7 Qa2+ 54. Kc3 Qxa5+ 55. Kb3 Qb5+ 56. Qb4 Qxb4+ 57. Kxb4 Re8) 48... Qa1 { Here is an interesting scenario where black tries to win a5. It is just an example variation of what might happen. } 49. Bd4 Qxa5 50. e6 Re8 51. Kf1 Rxe6 52. Qd2 Qxd2 53. Rxd2 Bxf3 54. Bc3 { Here White is threatening a mating net based on Ba5 Rd8 and Bb6 } 54... Bxg4 55. Rd8+ Ka7 56. Ba5 Rf6+ 57. Ke1 b5 58. cxb6+ Kb7 59. Rg8 Re6+ 60. Kf2 Re7 61. Rxg5 { Position is stable - no side can make progress }) 47. Bxg5 { This actually gives White's king the f4 square which may be critically needed } 47... Rh1 { Although this position looks very scary for White, it seems that Bd2 holds } (47... Bd5!? 48. Qf4 Qb2+ 49. Ke1 Rh1+ 50. Rf1 Qa1+ 51. Qc1 Qxe5+ 52. Qe3 { White is again stubbornly holding here }) 48. Bd2! { [%cal Gd2e1] } 48... Qd1+ 49. Ke3 $10 { White's king is safe enough here }) 44. e6 { A counter pawn sac - which ensures White immediately controls the h8 square and also opens up dangers for black on the g3-b8 diagonal potentially. } { [%csl Bh8][%cal Bd4h8] } 44... Qxe6 45. Kg3 { A very interesting move - and provides Rh2 in the case of Qh6 } { [%cal Ge6h6,Gf2h2] } (45. Re2?? { Although this move might seem plausible, it seems black is getting a winning advantage from the temporary pin } 45... Re8! 46. Kf2 Qh6 47. Ke1 (47. Kg2 Rh8 48. Bg1 Qh1+ 49. Kf2 Bxf3 { And black is winning } 50. Rd2 Qg2+ 51. Ke3 Qxg1+ 52. Kxf3 Rf8+ 53. Ke4 Rf4+ { This is an example of what can go disastrously wrong if White is not careful }) 47... Bxf3) 45... Qe7 (45... Qh6?! 46. Rh2 Qf8 47. f4 gxf4+ 48. Bxf4 { This position is about equal }) 46. Rh2 Qf7 { Threatening Qxf3+ } 47. f4 gxf4+ 48. Qxf4 Qe7 49. Rh5 Rf8 50. Rh7! (50. Qd4 Rf3+ { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gf3g3] } 51. Kh2 Rxe3 { And black wins }) 50... Rxf4 51. Rxe7 Re4 { Game agreed drawn here. After an exchange of rooks, even if White's king tries to win the b7 pawn in the resulting endgame by saccing the g-pawn, black can safely blockade by putting his bishop on b5. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "0:08:33-0:04:33"]
[Date "2016.11.24"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 10 - 24th Nov - Thanksgiving - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/CtnXiIkN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 { The Berlin Defence. Notes by Kingscrusher. Video at: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bik72MYqePU } 4. d3 { More popular is castling here. By playing d3 Magnus is avoiding the dreaded "Berlin endgame". See variation below. } (4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 { The dreaded Berlin endgame. Can be very solid and drawish. Magnus though needs a win, and perhaps wisely avoids this variation. }) 4... Bc5 5. c3 { The main move used } 5... O-O 6. Bg5 { Again castling has been delayed by Magnus. More usual is castling here. } 6... h6 7. Bh4 Be7 { The most common move. The bishop here steps back to be able to relieve the pin and also exchange off for White's dark squared bishop. } (7... g5 8. Bg3 d6 9. Nbd2 a6 { This occured in Anand vs Topalov 2005 which ended in a draw }) 8. O-O (8. Bxc6?! { Especially dubious if the idea is to try and win a pawn } 8... bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nxe4! $15 10. dxe4 Bxh4) 8... d6 9. Nbd2 Nh5 { Black does not mind the exchange of dark squared bishops. The f4 square looks nice for black right now. } 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 (10... Nxe7!? 11. Nxe5 { This is not such a big deal here because of Nf4 } 11... Nf4 12. Nef3 a6 13. Ba4 Nxd3 $10) 11. Nc4 { With the idea of Nc4-e3. But also the immediate threat is now Bxc6 and Nf3xe5 } (11. Nxe5?? Qxe5 { Protects the h5 knight } 12. Nc4 (12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nc4 Qg5 $19) 12... Qxb5) 11... Nf4 { The knight is securer now against any Nf3xe5 } (11... a6? 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Nfxe5 { The h5 knight is loose here } 13... dxe5 14. Qxh5 $16) (11... Re8? 12. Nfxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe8 Qxe8 14. Qxh5 $18) 12. Ne3 { White has also nice light square control to balance against the aggressive knight on f4. } 12... Qf6 13. g3 (13. Bxc6?! { This doesn't really achieve much it seems here. White would rather exchange off the light squared bishop for black's counterpart light squared bishop. } 13... bxc6 14. Kh1 Rd8 $15) 13... Nh3+ 14. Kh1 { Curiously the tempting Kg2 is not played. On h1 the King is slightly safer though. } 14... Ne7 { The knight heads for g6. But also by unblocking the c pawn, black supports c6 and d5. } 15. Bc4 c6 16. Bb3 Ng6 17. Qe2 a5 18. a4 { Preventing any queenside counterplay ideas of b5 } (18. a3 b5 19. Rad1 b4 20. Bc2 d5 $10) 18... Be6 19. Bxe6?! { A dubious move given the match circumstances - but based on an underestimation of tactical resources. On intuitive grounds. Intuitively White takes the plunge and allows potentially dangerous f-file pressure and related tactics that may be generated. On the upside, black's pawns in the centre may be more easily underminable in the future. However concretely black has some immediate fantastic resources which either secure a draw or a better position. } (19. Nd2! { Technically keeps the game alive. }) 19... fxe6 { Giving black potential f-file pressure but inflicting doubled pawns. Black now threatens Qxf3 } 20. Nd2 (20. Kg2?? Nhf4+ $19 21. gxf4 Nxf4+ 22. Kh1 Nxe2 $19) 20... d5?! { Given the match circumstances, investigation needs to be given to any potential forcing draws. It seems Nxf2+ is very promising for forcing a draw. However, it requires finding some very accurate resources. } (20... Nxf2+ 21. Kg2! { Technically the best move to simply allow a repetition draw. The alternative Kg1 seems to give black a clear advantage } (21. Kg1 Nh3+ 22. Kh1 (22. Kg2? Nhf4+ (22... Ngf4+! 23. gxf4 Nxf4+ 24. Rxf4 exf4 $17) 23. gxf4 Nxf4+ 24. Rxf4 exf4 25. Nc2 e5 $17 { Black is better here } 26. Kh1 g5 27. d4 Rae8 28. Qh5 Kh7 29. Re1 exd4 30. Nxd4 d5 31. h3 Qg6 { Black has great pawn inertia and prospects here }) 22... Nf2+ { With a draw by repetition ensuing which would favour Karjakin especially given he has the black pieces. To draw this game would have led him one step closer to securing the match. }) 21... Nh4+! { The tactical point here. Qg6+ will be dangerous if White takes the knight. } 22. gxh4? (22. Kg1 Nh3+ 23. Kh1 Nf2+ { With a draw by repetition } 24. Rxf2? (24. Kg1) 24... Qxf2 25. Qxf2 Rxf2 26. gxh4 Rxd2 $19) 22... Qg6+ 23. Ng4 Nxg4 $19) 21. Qh5?! { Hitting the knight on h3 but again allowing black to essentially force a draw if best play applied. } (21. f3 { Technically keeps the game alive again! } 21... Qd8 22. d4 $14 exd4 23. cxd4 dxe4 24. Nxe4 Qxd4 25. Nc4 Ne5 26. Ncd6 $14 Rad8) 21... Ng5?! { Maybe better was Nxf2+ where it seems black can safely do this based on certain tactical issues White has. } (21... Nxf2+ 22. Kg2 { White threatens here Ng4 to try and win the f2 knight. But black has a resource here. } (22. Kg1 Qg5! 23. Qxg5 Nh3+ 24. Kg2 Nxg5 $17) 22... Qf7! { Threatening Nf4+ winning the queen on h5 } 23. Kg1 (23. Ng4?? Nf4+ 24. gxf4 Qxh5) 23... Qf6 { Threatening Qg5 } 24. Kg2 { Threatening Ng4 but black now plays Qf7 again threatening Nf4+ to win the queen } (24. Rae1 Qg5 25. Qxg5 Nh3+ 26. Kg2 Nxg5 $10) (24. Ng4 Qg5 25. Qxg5 Nh3+ 26. Kg2 Nxg5 $17) 24... Qf7) 22. h4!? (22. Rae1! { Seems very strong because of Ng4 coming to maximise pressure on e5 } 22... Nf3 23. Ng4! Qg5 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. Nxf3 Rxf3 26. Rd1 $16) 22... Nf3 (22... Nh7 23. Ng4 $16 Qf7 24. Rae1 $16) 23. Nxf3 Qxf3+ 24. Qxf3 Rxf3 25. Kg2 Rf7 26. Rfe1 { Putting indirect pressure on the e5 pawn. The threat now is h5 and Ng4 to accelerate the e5 pressure. So in effect this move encourages black to play now h5 to stop h5 from White. } (26. h5!? Nf8 (26... Ne7!! 27. Ng4) 27. Ng4 Nd7 $10 28. Rfe1 { Threatening exd5 } 28... d4 (28... Re8 29. b4 $16) 29. Rec1 $16) 26... h5?! { To stop White playing h5 followed by Ng4 when e5 is weak. However in this position, the long term undermining operations for White can be two-fold - on the queenside with b4-b5 later hitting c6. And on the kingside later with f3-g4 for the h5 target. By creating the h5 target, it means that pressure can be exerted on both sides of the board for some time, to try and get the optimal point for a breakthrough. } (26... Raf8 27. Rf1 Kh7 28. h5 Nh8 29. Ng4 $18) 27. Nf1 Kf8 28. Nd2 Ke7 { The black king is looking to assist on the queenside later if necessary. } 29. Re2 Kd6 { The King can also help reinforce the e5 pawn. } 30. Nf3 Raf8 31. Ng5 Re7 32. Rae1 { Pressure increasing on e5 in some variations now. } 32... Rfe8 33. Nf3 Nh8 34. d4 { White is gaining a space advantage } 34... exd4 35. Nxd4 g6 (35... e5? 36. Nf5+ Ke6 37. Nxe7 Rxe7 $18) (35... c5? 36. Nb5+ Kd7 37. Rd1 Kc6 38. exd5+ exd5 39. Na7+ Kb6 (39... Kd6 40. Rxe7 Rxe7? (40... Kxe7 41. Rxd5 $18) 41. Nc8+ $18) 40. Rxe7 Rxe7 41. Nc8+ Kc7 42. Nxe7 $18) 36. Re3 Nf7 (36... e5?! { Although a tempting forcing move, there are certain downsides to this - the a5 pawn is weak and can be used to gain an important tempo - and the black pawns are slightly weaker and can be pressurised and undermined more easily, as the example variation shows. } 37. Nb3 b6 (37... Nf7 38. exd5 cxd5 39. Rd1 Rd8 40. Red3 Kc7 41. Nxa5 $18) 38. Rd1 Ke6 39. exd5+ cxd5 40. Nc1 Rd8 41. f4 Nf7 42. fxe5 Nxe5 { Black has an Isolated Queens Pawn (IQP) here now. } 43. Nd3 $16 Kd6 44. Nf4 Kc5 45. b3 $16 { White stands much better here }) 37. e5+ { Gaining a clear space advantage. } 37... Kd7 38. Rf3 { The rook has f6 in sight for infiltration. } 38... Nh6 39. Rf6 Rg7 (39... Nf5? 40. Rxg6 Nxd4 41. cxd4 $18) 40. b4 { White is increasing the grip on key dark squares on the queenside with this move. } 40... axb4 $7 { Virtually forced. } (40... b6? 41. bxa5 bxa5 42. Rb1 $18 Kc7 (42... Rc8 43. Rb7+ Rc7 44. Rxc7+ Kxc7 45. Nxe6+ $18) 43. Rxe6 $18) 41. cxb4 Ng8 (41... b6? 42. a5 bxa5 43. Ra1 Ra8 44. Rxa5 Rxa5 45. bxa5 Ng4 46. Rxe6 $18) 42. Rf3 Nh6 43. a5 { Increasing the dark square grip. With b6 securer, the knight can now come to c5 later, without being kicked by b6 as easily. Blacks fixed targets b7 and e6 make this a nice torture scenario for Magnus to exert pressure from. } 43... Nf5 44. Nb3 Kc7 45. Nc5 Kb8 46. Rb1 { b5 seems imminent now to further pressurise b7 and also e6 via the b6 square. } 46... Ka7 47. Rd3 { Carefully preparing b5 } (47. b5?! cxb5 48. Rxb5? Nd4 { Forking the rooks } 49. Rb6 Nxf3 $19) 47... Rc7 48. Ra3 (48. b5!? { This doesn't seem the best moment for b5 because black has pressure on the c-file } 48... cxb5 49. Rxb5 Ree7 50. Rd2 Rc8 51. Rd1 Rcc7 52. Rd2 Rc8 53. Nd3 Rc4 { It is not entirely clear how White proceeds here }) 48... Nd4 49. Rd1 Nf5 50. Kh3 { White is essentially carefully preparing b5 by first making sure there is also a dual positional threat on the other side of the board which is using the f-file potentially. By placing the king here, f3 and g4 will reduce the impact of black's knight or win the f-file as a second front. If the knight is less effective, White can then revert back to the b5 breakthrough. h5 prompted earlier in the game has made it possible to make use of the h5 pawn for undermining or the threat of undermining with a prepared g4. } 50... Nh6 51. f3 Rf7 52. Rd4 Nf5 (52... Rfe7? 53. Rf4 Rf7 54. Rf6 Rxf6 55. exf6 e5 56. Rb3 { b5 now is far more effective than other earlier positions } 56... e4 57. fxe4 Ng4 58. b5 cxb5 59. Rxb5 Nxf6 60. e5 Rxe5? (60... Ng4 61. e6 Re7 62. Kg2 d4 63. Kf3 $16) 61. Rxb7+ Ka8 62. a6 $18) 53. Rd2 Rh7 54. Rb3 Ree7 (54... Rc7!? 55. g4 hxg4+? { This sort of move would make White's task much clearer as the f-file can become useful to White very quickly. } (55... Nh6 56. Kg3 Rf7 57. Rdb2 Rc7 58. Nd3 Rce7 $16) 56. fxg4 Nh6 57. Rf3 { White can cleverly use the f-file here with advantage } 57... Nf7 58. Nd3 $18 Nd8 59. Rf6) 55. Rdd3 Rh8 56. Rb1 Rhh7? { It seems this move amplifies the effectiveness of playing b5 now. The rook on h7 seems less well placed for the upcoming b5 break. } (56... Rf8! 57. b5 cxb5 58. Rxb5 Rc8 { The rook can usefully try and make use of the c-file as a beneficiary of the b5 break. } 59. g4 Nh6 60. Rdb3 hxg4+ 61. fxg4 Rcc7 { Black can stubbornly hold on here }) 57. b5 { Magnus chooses this moment for the b5 breakthrough. } 57... cxb5 58. Rxb5 d4 (58... Rh8? 59. Rb6 Rhe8 60. g4 Nh6 61. Rdb3 Rc8 62. Nxe6 $18) (58... Rc7? 59. Nxe6 Rc1 60. Rbxd5 $18) 59. Rb6 Rc7 60. Nxe6 Rc3 61. Nf4 Rhc7 62. Nd5 (62. Rxg6!? { This seems very promising } 62... Rxd3 63. Nxd3 Rc3 64. Rf6 Ne7 65. Nf4 Re3 66. e6 d3 67. Rf8 Rxf3 68. Rd8 Re3 69. Rxd3 $18) 62... Rxd3 63. Nxc7 Kb8 (63... Rxf3? 64. Nb5+ Kb8 (64... Ka8 65. Rf6 { Threatening Rf8 mating } 65... Nd6 66. Nxd6 $18) 65. a6! $18 d3 66. Rxb7+ Kc8 67. Rc7+ Kb8 68. a7+ Ka8 69. Rc8+ Kb7 70. a8=Q+ $18) 64. Nb5 { Threatening a6 } 64... Kc8 65. Rxg6 Rxf3 66. Kg2 Rb3 67. Nd6+ Nxd6 68. Rxd6 Re3 (68... Kc7 { Example continuation given } 69. Rxd4 Rb5 70. Kf3 Rxe5 71. Ra4 Rc5 72. Kf4 Kd7 73. a6 bxa6 74. Rxa6 Ke7 75. Rg6 Rc8 76. Rg5 Rh8 77. Kf5 Kf7 78. Rg6 Kf8 79. Ra6 Ke8? (79... Ke7 80. Ra7+ Kd6 81. Kg6 Rg8+ 82. Rg7 Rh8 83. Kf7 Kc7 84. Rg5 Rh7+ 85. Kg8 Rh6 86. Kg7 Rd6 87. Rc5+ Kb6 88. Rxh5 $18) 80. Ra8+ $18) 69. e6 Kc7 (69... d3 70. Kf2 Re5 (70... Re2+ 71. Kf3 Kc7 72. Rxd3 Rxe6 73. Rd5 $18 Rf6+ 74. Ke4 Rh6 $18) 71. Kf3 Kc7 72. Rxd3 Rxe6 73. Kf4 Kc6 74. Rb3 Re7 75. Rb6+ Kc7 76. Rb5 $18) 70. Rxd4 Rxe6 71. Rd5 Rh6 72. Kf3 Kb8 73. Kf4 Ka7 74. Kg5 Rh8 75. Kf6! { 1-0 Game ended here. Rest is analysis. This move avoids any issues with Rg8+ and Rxg3 } (75. Kg6? Rg8+ 76. Kxh5 Rxg3 { Unnecessary to lose the g-pawn like this, but even this is still winning for White. } 77. Kh6 Ka6 78. h5 Rg1 79. Kh7 Rg3 80. h6 Rg1 81. Kh8 Ka7 82. h7 Rg2 83. Rf5 Rg1 84. Rf8 Rg5 85. Rg8 Rxa5 86. Kg7 $18 Rh5 87. h8=Q Rxh8 88. Rxh8 Ka6 89. Kf7 $18) 1-0


