[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "2016.11.26"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C84"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed, Martinez Variation"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 11 - 26th Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/Zos4PiR0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 { Sergey sticks to the move which he has had the most experience with - 1.e4 } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Ruy Lopez } 3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 { The Ruy Lopez Closed - Martinez Variation. More often played generally are the moves Re1 or Bxc6. } 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 { By protecting e5, Na5 becomes possible. } 8. a3 { Giving the bishop an escape square on a2 if Black plays Na5 } 8... O-O 9. Nc3 { Keeping a firm grip on the d5 square } 9... Be6 { Magnus varies from Game 2 where he played Na5 } 10. Nd5 { The most common move here } 10... Nd4 { Black doesn't mind the possibility of doubled pawns here } 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Nxf6+ (12. Nxe7+!? Qxe7 13. Bg5 c5 14. f4?! (14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. f4 h6 16. Bh4 e5 17. f5 $10) 14... Bxb3 $10) 12... Bxf6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 { After this flurry of exchanges, the black Kingside is slightly weaker with one less defensive pawn. White focuses on the Kingside now } 14. f4 c5 { Not just reinforcing d4 but also c4 is coming soon } 15. Qg4 { Hitting the e6 pawn but also helping support f5 } 15... Qd7 16. f5 Rae8 (16... exf5!? 17. Rxf5 Rf7 18. Bd2 g6 19. h3 Raf8 20. Bf4 Bd8 21. Rxf7 Rxf7 22. Bg3 Qxg4 23. hxg4 Rd7 $10) (16... e5!? 17. Rf3 d5 18. Rh3 dxe4 19. dxe4 Qf7 20. Bd2 Rfd8 $10) 17. Bd2 c4 { Magnus plays a logical pawn structure undermining plan. } 18. h3 { Protecting the queen } 18... c3 19. bxc3 d5 { Spicing things up a little } (19... dxc3 20. Be3 d5 21. Bc5 Rf7 22. Rae1 e5 $10) 20. Bg5 (20. cxd4? Bxd4+ 21. Kh1 exf5 22. exf5 Bxa1 $19) (20. fxe6!? Qxe6 21. Qxe6+ Rxe6 22. exd5 Re2 23. Rf2 Rxf2 24. Kxf2 dxc3 25. Be1 Rd8 26. Kf3 $10) 20... Bxg5 21. Qxg5 dxe4 22. fxe6 Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Qxe6 24. cxd4 e3 { Magnus creates some potential problems with this passed pawn } (24... exd3!? 25. cxd3 Qe3+ 26. Qxe3 Rxe3 27. Rd1 Re2 $10 28. Rc1 Ra2 29. Rc8+ Kf7 30. Rc7+ Kf8 $10) 25. Re1 h6 (25... e2!? 26. Qd2 h6 27. Kf2? Qf6+ 28. Kg1 Qxd4+) 26. Qh5 e2 { Black threatens Qe3+ here with invasion points on f2 or d2 to support the passed pawn } 27. Qf3 { Defending against Qe3+ } (27. d5? Qe3+ 28. Kh2 Qf4+ 29. Kg1 Qe3+ 30. Kh2 Re5 31. Qf3 Qd2 32. Qf2 Re8 33. d6 Qxc2 $15) 27... a5 28. c3 { Holding against a possible b4 a bit tighter } 28... Qa2 { Hitting a3 and also sometimes Qd2 is useful } 29. Qc6 Re6 30. Qc8+ (30. Qxb5? Qd2 31. Qb1 Qxc3 $17) 30... Kh7 31. c4 { Hitting the rook now which is not protected } 31... Qd2 32. Qxe6 Qxe1+ 33. Kh2 Qf2 34. Qe4+ { Draw by perpetual check } 1/2-1/2


