[Event "Carlsen - Karjakin World Championship"]
[Site "1:38:33-1:28:33"]
[Date "2016.11.28"]
[Round "12"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Sergey Karjakin"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2016 Carlsen vs Karjakin - Post-mortem Analysis"]
[ChapterName "Game 12 - 28th Nov - Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/vENPCM25/1fgYVe4c"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 { The Berlin defence - a reputation of solidity and dullness which is well deserved. } 4. O-O { The "main line" move, which is known to end up in approximate equality. } 4... Nxe4 5. Re1 { Another popular move here is d4 } (5. d4 { The absolute main line move goes to an endgame } 5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. Rd1 { The Berlin endgame }) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 Bf6 10. Re1 { No suprise with Re2 this game like in Game 3. The prospects of excitement are limited because of the one shared file. } 10... Re8 11. Bf4 { A threat - Bxd6 to double black's pawns. } 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 { The first exciting moment - the d pawn is hanging } 12... Ne8 { Avoiding Bxd6 and the dreaded doubled pawns that would result. Black temporarily looks a bit passive but there is only one shared file here. } (12... Bxd4 13. c3 (13. Bxd6 cxd6 (13... Bxb2? 14. Bxc7 Qf8 15. Nc3 Bxa1 16. Qxa1 $18) 14. c3) 13... Bf6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Na3 $14 { White has a small advantage here } 15... d5 16. Nb5 g6 17. Qd2 d4 18. Nxd4 $14) 13. c3 { Securing the d4 pawn against Bxd4 and blunting the f6 bishop. Also c3 means that the c2 square can be used for a knight. } 13... d5 14. Bd3 g6 15. Na3 { More interesting than Nd2. White might threaten Nb5 in some positions. } (15. Nd2!? { This seems a solid alternative } 15... Ng7 16. Qe2 c6 17. Re1 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. Nf3 $10 Ng7 20. Be5 Bxe5 21. Qxe5 Qb6 $13) 15... c6 { Black avoids any Nb5 possibility } (15... Ng7!? { This was also possible because Nb5 isn't such a big deal } 16. Nb5 Ne6 { Defending c7 in time } 17. Be5 a6 18. Na3 c6 $10) 16. Nc2 Ng7 { Preparing Bf5 } 17. Qd2 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. Ne3 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Qe7 { This is not the most exciting game ever played } 21. Qxe7 Bxe7 22. Re1 Bf8 23. Kf1 f6 24. g4 { Magnus often puts pawns on the opposite colour to the opponent's bishop in endgame scenarios. The pawns are fundamentally safer there. Here they also don't hem in White's dark squared bishop either. } 24... Kf7 25. h3 { Another pawn on a light square } 25... Re8 26. Rxe8 Kxe8 { Play needs to continue at least until move 30 for a draw to be agreed according to the rules of the match. } 27. Ke2 { A game where not much happened except rapid simplification. Whilst many tournament players often try and create "Imbalances", this game shows the opposite - the maintenance of "balance" - and solid risk free play that results which features exchanging down to a more simplified and risk free position where a draw can be naturally agreed. The symmetrical pawn structure here also serves to minimise risk for both sides. } 27... Kd7 28. Kd3 Ke6 29. a4 a6 30. f3 Be7 { Draw agreed. Not the most "mega exciting" game of all time - but both players seem more than happy to enter the tiebreaks for faster time controls. } 1/2-1/2


