1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. Bf4 d5 6. Qb3 dxc4 (6... c5 7. cxd5 (7. dxc5 d4 8. Nd5 Na6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Qa3 b6 11. c6 Re8 12. Be5 Bxe5 13. Nxe5 Qc7 14. f4 f6 15. Nf3 e5 $17) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 e5 10. Bxe5 Bxe5 $15) 7. Qxc4 c6 (7... Bf5 8. e3 c6 $14) 8. e4 Nbd7 9. Rd1 (9. h3 Nh5 10. Bh2 Nb6 11. Qd3 $14) 9... Nb6 10. Qc5 Bg4 11. Bg5 { Be2 more solid but who would expect Fischer's next move.Be2 is a safe move based on higher principles of opening - not moving same piece twice, trying to castle early } (11. Be2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nfd7 13. Qa3 e5 14. dxe5 Re8 15. O-O Qe7 16. Qxe7 Rxe7 17. e6 Rxe6 18. Bg4 Re7 $14) 11... Na4 { Brilliant move that the latest engine technology approves } { [%cal Yb6a4] } (11... h6 12. Bh4 (12. Be3 Nfd7 13. Qb4 Be6 14. h3 $10) 12... Re8 13. Be2 g5 14. Bg3 $10) (11... Nfd7 12. Bxe7 (12. Qxe7 Qxe7 13. Bxe7 Rfe8 14. Bg5 f5 $10) 12... Nxc5 13. Bxd8 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Raxd8 $17) 12. Qa3 { On 12.Nxa4 Nxe4 and White faces considerable difficulties. } (12. Nxa4 Nxe4 13. Bxe7 (13. Qxe7 Nxg5 14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Nxg5 Rfe8+ 16. Kd2 Bxd1 17. Kxd1 Rxd4+ 18. Kc2 Rxa4) (13. Qc1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Qxa4 $17) (13. Qb4 Nxg5 14. Nxg5 Bxd1 15. Kxd1 b5 16. Nc5 Bxd4 17. Kc2 a5 18. Qa3 Qd5 19. Nce4 h6 20. Qb3 hxg5 $17) (13. Qc2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nxg5 15. Bg2 Qd5 16. O-O Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 (17. Kh1 Qh5 18. h3 Nxd4 $17) 17... Qxf3 $17) 13... Qc7 14. Qa3 (14. Bd6 Nxd6 15. Be2 Rfe8 16. Kf1 b6 $17) 14... Rfe8 15. Bb4 Ng3+ 16. Kd2 Nxh1 $17) 12... Nxc3 { Counter intuitive - it seems to be strengthening the center but creates more weaknesses actually exploitable } 13. bxc3 (13. Qxc3 Nxe4 14. Qc1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qa5+ 16. Bd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Qxa2 $17) 13... Nxe4 14. Bxe7 (14. Be2 Nxg5 15. Nxg5 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 e5 17. h4 exd4 $17) 14... Qb6 15. Bc4 (15. Bxf8 Bxf8 16. Qb3 Nxc3 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Ra1 Bb4 $17) 15... Nxc3 16. Bc5 (16. Qxc3 Rae8 17. O-O Rxe7 $17) (16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. Qc1 Nxd1 18. Qxd1 Qb4+ 19. Kf1 Qxc4+ $17) 16... Rfe8+ 17. Kf1 Be6 (17... Qc7 18. Qxc3 b6 19. Ba3 c5 20. h3 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Bxd1 22. Nf3 Bxf3 23. Bb2 Qe5 24. Qxe5 Rxe5 25. Bxe5 $16) 18. Bxb6 (18. Bxe6 Qb5+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Ng3+ 21. Kg1 Qf1+ 22. Rxf1 Ne2#) (18. Bb3 Qb5+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Ng3+ 21. Kg1 Qf1+ 22. Rxf1 Ne2#) 18... Bxc4+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Nxd4+ { This tactical scenario, where a king is repeatedly revealed to checks, is sometimes called a "windmill." } 21. Kg1 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nc3+ 23. Kg1 axb6 24. Qb4 Ra4 25. Qxb6 Nxd1 26. h3 Rxa2 27. Kh2 Nxf2 28. Re1 Rxe1 29. Qd8+ Bf8 30. Nxe1 Bd5 31. Nf3 Ne4 32. Qb8 b5 { Every piece and pawn of the black camp is defended.The white queen has nothing to do. } 33. h4 h5 (33... b4 34. h5 b3 35. Kh3 gxh5 $17) 34. Ne5 Kg7 35. Kg1 (35. Qc7 Bd6 $17) 35... Bc5+ 36. Kf1 Ng3+ { Now Byrne is hopelessly entangled in Fischer's mating net. } 37. Ke1 Bb4+ 38. Kd1 Bb3+ 39. Kc1 Ne2+ 40. Kb1 Nc3+ 41. Kc1 Rc2# { The Game of the Century is a chess game that was won by the 13-year-old future world champion Bobby Fischer against Donald Byrne in the Rosenwald Memorial Tournament at the Marshall Chess Club in New York City on October 17, 1956.In Chess Review, Hans Kmoch dubbed it "The Game of the Century" and wrote: "The following game, a stunning masterpiece of combination play performed by a boy of 13 against a formidable opponent, matches the finest on record in the history of chess prodigies } 0-1


