[Event "Reddit : Precise move orders against the Caro-Kann: Chapter 1 - Caro-Kann main line"]
[Date "2016.09.16"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B15"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Gurgenidze System"]
[StudyName "Reddit : Precise move orders against the Caro-Kann"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 1 - Caro-Kann main line"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/UGiaMAsW/bdYEwqYY"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]
[UTCDate "2016.09.16"]
[UTCTime "14:34:41"]

1. e4 c6 { This study was inspired by a reddit thread: https://www.reddit.com/r/chess/comments/52y823/why_move_order_matters_in_the_classical_mainline/?st=it5wtalk&sh=648ebc75 } 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 { There are some arguments than Nd2 might be more precise. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bukhuti_Gurgenidze
"His name is attached to the Gurgenidze Variation in the Sicilian Defence (1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4.0-0 Bg7 5.Re1 e5 6.b4).[3] and in the Caro-Kann Gurgenidze Variation: 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 g6; it is because of this variation, originated by Bukhuti Gurgenidze, that 3.Nc3 fell from favour in the 1970s. 3.Nd2 has since been regarded as the accurate way to reach the positions arising from ....dxe4. After 3.Nd2,....g6 is met by 4.c3, when the fianchettoed bishop has little to do."
Note also than Nc3 also encourages the possibility of b5 See : https://www.newinchess.com/Archives/SOSList.aspx?OpeningID=4
"SOS Vol. 7 Chapter 7 by: Adrian Mikhalchishin The Caro-Kann of Bukhuti Gurgenidze 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 b5!? Caro-Kann Defence
1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 b5!?" } (3. Nd2 g6 4. c3 { Blunts the fianchetto bishop } 4... Bg7 5. Ngf3 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Bd3) 3... g6 (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 { This is how the mainline usually starts, and is the most accurate move order. } (6. Nf3 Nf6 7. h4 Nh5 { Interestingly.... Robert James Fischer vs Robert Henry Steinmeyer
US Championship (1963/64) - had h6 here... Also Robert James Fischer vs Luis Loayza New York simul (1965) - black had the chance to play Nh5 } (7... h6 8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 (9... Qxd4 10. Nxf7 { Nice trap line! } 10... Kxf7 11. Bg6+ Bxg6 12. Qxd4 { Winning queen! }) 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. f4 $14 { This line is considered good for White. He has more space and a development advantage. } { It does seem like a nice attacking bind here, easier to play for White. } 11... c5 12. Be3 cxd4 13. Bxd4 { This is okay for White. } 13... Nxe5 14. fxe5 Nd5 15. e6 { Crushing! } 15... Qa5+ 16. Bc3 Qc5 17. exf7+ Kxf7 18. Qf5+ Kg8 19. O-O-O Qe3+ 20. Bd2 Qxg3 21. Qxd5+ Kh7 22. Rde1) 8. Ne2 (8. Nxh5 Bxh5 $10 { black has no problems here. }) (8. Bc4 Nxg3 (8... Nd7? 9. Nxh5 Bxh5 10. g4 Bxg4 11. Bxf7+ $16 { white gets a nice position here. Mamedov - Anand 2009 }) 9. fxg3 e6 $13) (8. Bd3 { This might be best but it does look a bit ugly! } 8... Nxg3 9. fxg3 { Maybe White has some dynamic compensation here for the doubled pawns... Engine thinks its okay for White } 9... e6 $13 (9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. O-O Nd7 12. Bf4 Be7 13. g4 Bxh4 14. g5 h6 15. g6 O-O 16. Qe4 Bf6 17. Rae1 $10 { White is doing okay here }) 10. Bxg6 hxg6 11. Bf4) 8... e6 9. Nf4!? (9. g4 Nf6 10. h5 Be4 11. Ng3)) 6... h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 (7... Nf6) 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3) (3... b5!? { Another interesting idea from Gurgenidze } 4. e5 (4. exd5 b4 5. Na4 cxd5 6. Nc5 e6 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Nxd7 Nxd7 { Black seems to have nearly equalised here }) 4... Bf5) *


