{ Karl Ernst Adolf Anderssen was born in Breslau.He was one of the strongest
players of his day and was regarded by some to be the World Champion after his
victory in the London (1851) tournament.1,2 He lost this honor in the
Anderssen - Morphy (1858) match.One year later, however, Paul Morphy retired
from international chess, and Anderssen was able to regain his reputation as
the world's leading player, drawing Ignatz von Kolisch in Paris 1860 (+5 -5 =1)
,3 and winning the Anderssen - Kolisch (1861) match in London (+4 -3 =2).
Anderssen also won the London International 1862 over Louis Paulsen, who
finished second.2 He subsequently drew him in the Anderssen - Paulsen (1862)
match (+3 -3 =2).In 1866, Anderssen narrowly lost a match with Wilhelm
Steinitz (+6 -8 =0).He scored his final great success by winning the
Baden-Baden (1870) tournament, ahead of Steinitz and Joseph Henry Blackburne.
4 Anderssen is regarded as the quintessential Romantic, and his sacrificial
brilliancies such as The Immortal Game (Anderssen vs Kieseritzky, 1851) and
The Evergreen Game (Anderssen vs Dufresne, 1852) have stood the test of time. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Bc4 Qh4+ (3... Nc6 4. d4 (4. Nf3 g5 $17) 4... Qh4+ 5. Kf1 d6 $17) 4. Kf1 b5 (4... d6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nf3 Qh6 7. d4 $15) 5. Bxb5 Nf6 6. Nf3 Qh6 7. d3 (7. d4 Nxe4 8. Qe2 f5 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. d5) (7. Nc3 c6 8. Ba4 Bc5 9. e5 Ng4 10. Ne4 Na6 11. b4 Bxb4 12. h3 Nc5 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14. Rb1 $14) 7... Nh5 { threat of Ng3 check } (7... c6 8. Ba4 Bc5 9. Qe1 Ng4 10. Nc3 Bf2 11. Qe2 Be3) 8. Nh4 Qg5 9. Nf5 (9. Nf3 Qxb5 $17) 9... c6 10. g4 Nf6 11. Rg1 cxb5 12. h4 Qg6 13. h5 Qg5 14. Qf3 Ng8 15. Bxf4 Qf6 16. Nc3 Bc5 17. Nd5 (17. d4 Bb6 (17... Bxd4 18. Nd5 Qc6 19. Nc7+ Kd8 20. Nxd4 $16) 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Nxg7+ Kf8 20. Bd6+ Kxg7 21. g5 { forced mate in 5 } 21... f6 22. gxf6+ Kf7 23. Rg7+ Ke6 24. Nf4+ Kxd6 25. e5+ Kc7 26. Ne6#) 17... Qxb2 18. Bd6 { inaccuracy } (18. Re1 { delayed
gratfiication of Bd6 is stronger } 18... Bb7 19. Bd6 Bxg1 20. Qf4 Bb6 21. Qg5 Nc6 22. Nxg7+ Qxg7 23. Qxg7 O-O-O 24. Nxb6+ axb6 25. Qxh8 $16) 18... Bxg1 { mistake but
black is losing in fact } (18... Qxa1+ 19. Ke2 Qb2 (19... Qxg1 20. Nxg7+ Kd8 21. Bc7#) (19... Bxg1 20. e5) 20. Kd2 { This is still winning for White in fact } (20. Bxc5 Qxc2+ 21. Kf1 Qxc5 $17 22. Qf4 Kd8 23. Nd6 Ne7 24. Nxf7+ Ke8 25. Nd6+) 20... Bxg1 (20... Bb4+ 21. Bxb4 $16) (20... Bxd6 21. Nxd6+ Kd8 22. Nxf7+ Ke8 23. Nd6+ Kd8 24. Qf8#) 21. e5 { threat of Nxg7+ and Bc7 mate } 21... Ba6 (21... f6 22. Nxg7+ Kf7 23. Nxf6 Be3+ 24. Kxe3 Qc1+ 25. Kf2 Qxc2+ 26. Kg3 $16) 22. Bb4 Nh6 (22... Qxe5 23. Nd6+ Qxd6 24. Bxd6 Nc6 25. Nc7+ Kd8 26. Qxf7 Nge7 27. Nxa8 $16) 23. Nd6+ Kf8 24. g5 $16) 19. e5 { blocking Q on b2 protecting g7 } (19. Re1 Ba6 20. Bb4 { Nd6 check threat } 20... Nc6 21. Nd6+ Kd8 22. Nxf7+ Kc8 23. Nd6+ Kb8 24. Qf8+ Nd8 25. Qxd8+ Bc8 26. Qxc8#) 19... Qxa1+ 20. Ke2 Na6 (20... Ba6 21. Nc7+ Kd8 22. Nxa6 Qc3 (22... Qxa2 23. Nb4) (22... Bb6 23. Qxa8 Qc3 24. Nb4 Bc7 25. Kd1 Bxd6 26. Nxd6 Ne7 27. Qxb8+ Nc8 28. a3 f6 (28... Qxa3 29. Nc6+ dxc6 30. Qxc8+ Ke7 31. Nf5#) 29. Nf7+ Ke8 30. Nxh8 $16) 23. Bc7+ Qxc7 24. Nxc7 Nc6 25. Nxa8 $16) (20... Qb2 21. Nxg7+ Kd8 22. Bc7#) 21. Nxg7+ Kd8 22. Qf6+ Nxf6 23. Be7# { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


