{ Emanuel Lasker was the second official World Chess Champion, reigning for a record 27 years after he defeated the first World Champion, Wilhelm Steinitz, in 1894.Statistician Jeff Sonas of Chessmetrics writes, "if you look across players' entire careers, there is a significant amount of statistical evidence to support the claim that Emanuel Lasker was, in fact, the most dominant player of all time. By Chess Statisician Jeoff Sonas's reckoning, Lasker was the No.1 player in the world for a total of 24.3 years between 1890 and 1926. }
1. f4 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. Bd3 { [%cal Yb2h8,Yd3h7] } 5... b6 6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne2 c5 10. Ng3 Qc7 11. Ne5 (11. Qe2 Bd6 12. Rae1 $10) 11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5 (12. fxe5 Nd7 13. Qh5 g6 (13... h6 14. Rf4 c4 15. bxc4 Bg5 16. Rg4 f5 (16... dxc4 17. Rxg5 cxd3 18. Qxh6 g6 19. Nh5 Qxe5 20. Bxe5 Nxe5 21. Nf6#) 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Qxh6 Bxb2 19. c3 Rf7 20. Rf1 Ne5 21. Qh7+ Kf8 22. Qxg7+ Ke7 23. Rxf7+ Nxf7 24. Rf4 Rf8 25. Bg6 dxc4 26. Rxf7+ Rxf7 27. Qxf7+ Kd6 28. Qf8+ Qe7 29. Qf4+ Kc6 30. Qxc4+ $16) 14. Qh6 Rfc8 15. Rxf7 Kxf7 16. Qxh7+ Ke8 17. Bxg6+ Kd8 18. Qf7 Qc6 (18... Nxe5 19. Qe8#) 19. Qe8+ Kc7 20. Qxe7 Rf8 21. d4 Rad8 22. Nh5 $18) 12... Qc6 13. Qe2 (13. f5 c4 14. Be2 (14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Be2 (15. Qe2 cxd3 16. cxd3 Ba6 $17) 15... Qxg2#) 14... Nd7 15. Bb2 Bf6 $10) (13. Nh5 d4 14. Rf2 dxe3 15. dxe3 Nxh5 16. Qxh5 f5 $14) 13... a6 (13... c4 14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Rac8 16. Bd3 $16) 14. Nh5 Nxh5 { [%cal Yf6h5] } (14... Rfe8 15. Nxg7 Kxg7 16. Qg4+ Kf8 17. Qg5 Red8 (17... Ng8 18. Qg7#) 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Qxf6 $16) 15. Bxh7+ (15. Qxh5 f5 $10 { no fun to be had here }) 15... Kxh7 16. Qxh5+ Kg8 17. Bxg7 { Threat is now Qh8 checkmate } { [%cal Ye5g7] } 17... Kxg7 (17... f6 18. Rf3 Rf7 (18... Kxg7 19. Rg3#) (18... Qe8 19. Qh8+ Kf7 20. Qh7 Rg8 21. Bh6+ Rg7 22. Qxg7#) 19. Qh8#) 18. Qg4+ Kh7 (18... Kf6 19. Qg5#) 19. Rf3 { [%cal Yf3h3,Be6e5,Bc6h6] } 19... e5 (19... Rg8 20. Rh3+ Bh4 21. Rxh4# { lawnmower mate pattern }) 20. Rh3+ Qh6 21. Rxh6+ Kxh6 22. Qd7 { [%cal Yd7b7,Yd7e7] } (22. f5 Bf6 $10) (22. Rf1 f5 23. Qh3+ Kg6 24. Qg3+ Kf7 25. fxe5 Ke6 26. Qg6+ Kd7 27. Rxf5 Rxf5 28. Qxf5+ Kc7 29. Qf7 $16) (22. Qh3+ Kg7 23. Rf1 Bf6 24. Qg4+ Kh8 25. Rf3 Bg7 26. Rh3+ Kg8 27. Rg3 exf4 28. Qxg7#) 22... Bf6 23. Qxb7 Kg7 24. Rf1 Rab8 25. Qd7 (25. Qxd5 $16) 25... Rfd8 26. Qg4+ Kf8 27. fxe5 Bg7 28. e6 Rb7 (28... f6 29. e7+ Kxe7 30. Qxg7+ Ke8 31. Rxf6 c4 32. Rf8#) 29. Qg6 f6 30. Rxf6+ Bxf6 31. Qxf6+ Ke8 (31... Kg8 32. Qxd8+ $16) 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qg7+ Kxe6 34. Qxb7 Rd6 35. Qxa6 d4 36. exd4 cxd4 37. h4 d3 38. Qxd3 { A master of win probability adjusting openings and play to opponents } 1-0


