[FEN "4q2k/4P1p1/5n1p/1pBppQ2/1P2r3/6PP/6K1/5R2 w - - 0 46"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ [#] }
46. Qxf6 (46. h4) 46... gxf6 47. Rxf6 { Joining forces with the bishop on c5 for that
killer common f8 square } 47... Qh5 (47... Re2+ 48. Kf1 Kg7 49. Rf8 Qh5 50. e8=Q $16) 48. Rf8+ Kg7 49. e8=Q { Not minding some checks } 49... Re2+ 50. Kf1 { strongest move } (50. Kh1 { This is a bad idea - you are offering too much teamwork and "killer
common squares" to the opponent here after Qxh3+ and the g2 square in
particular means Qg2 and you get mated! Ooopsie! } 50... Qxh3+ 51. Kg1 Qg2#) (50. Kg1 { Black has the possibility of a perpetual check starting with Re1 check if you
play your King here } 50... Rb2 51. Qd7+ Kg6 52. Qf7+ Kg5 53. Be3#) 50... Qxh3+ (50... Qxe8 51. Rxe8 $16) 51. Kxe2 Qg2+ 52. Rf2 Qe4+ 53. Kd2 { "It is your game" - and
offers King and a respectful hug after The checks have run out.
Congratulations White wins now as Black resigns :) } 53... Qg6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "Biel Interzonal"]
[Site "Biel SUI"]
[Date "1993.07.16"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Vassily Ivanchuk"]
[Black "Patrick Wolff"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D20"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Accepted: Central Variation, Modern Defense"]
[StudyName "Queen's Gambit Netflix series games and analysis"]
[ChapterName "Vassily Ivanchuk - Patrick Wolff"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Q1Loag5s/c0tkqOBu"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nc6 4. Be3 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. d5 Ne7 7. Bxc4 Ng6 { [%cal Yb8c6,Yc6e7,Ye7g6] } 8. f3 Bd6 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. Nge2 a6 11. Bb3 b5 12. a4 O-O 13. O-O Qe7 14. Rac1 Nh5 15. g3 h6 16. Bc2 Rab8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra1 Ra8 19. Bd3 Bb4 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Qc2 Bc5 22. Nd1 Bd6 23. Nf2 Nhf4 24. Rc1 Qg5 25. Kh1 Qh5 26. Ng1 Nxd3 27. Nxd3 f5 28. Nc5 Bc8 29. Rf1 Ne7 30. Qd3 fxe4 31. fxe4 Qg6 32. Kg2 Kh7 33. Nf3 Ng8 34. Nh4 Qg4 35. Nf5 Nf6 36. h3 Qg6 37. g4 Bxc5 38. Bxc5 Ra4 39. Rf3 Rc4 40. Be7 Bxf5 41. Rxf5 Rd4 42. Qe3 Rxe4 43. Qf3 Rf4 44. Rxf4 exf4 45. Bxf6 Qxf6 46. Qd3+ Qg6 47. Qe2 c6 48. Kf3 cxd5 49. Kxf4 Qf6+ 50. Kg3 Qd6+ 51. Kf3 b4 52. h4 Qf6+ 53. Kg3 Qd6+ 54. Kf3 Qf6+ 55. Kg3 g6 56. Qe8 Qd6+ 57. Kf3 Kg7 58. g5 hxg5 59. hxg5 d4 60. Qe4 d3 61. Qb7+ Kf8 62. Qc8+ Ke7 63. Qb7+ Ke6 64. Qe4+ Kd7 65. Qb7+ Kd8 66. Qa8+ Kc7 67. Qa7+ Kc8 68. Qa8+ Kc7 69. Qa7+ Kc6 70. Qa6+ Kc5 71. Qxd6+ Kxd6 72. Ke3 Ke5 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Netflix Series The Queen's Gambit 2020"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "2020.10.29"]
[White "Harmon, Elizabeth"]
[Black "Borgov, Vasily"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "-"]
[BlackElo "-"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D20"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Accepted: Central Variation, McDonnell Defense"]
[StudyName "Queen's Gambit Netflix series games and analysis"]
[ChapterName "Harmon, Elizabeth - Borgov, Vasily"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Q1Loag5s/PcFENL2S"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Kingscrusher-YouTube"]

1. d4 { Game was based on Ivanchuk vs Wolff played in 1993 } 1... d5 2. c4 e5 { one of my absolute favourite systems with black in blitz - check my albin counter gambit playlist } (2... dxc4 3. e4 Nc6 4. Be3 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. d5 Ne7 7. Bxc4 Ng6 { Kingscrusher tango system d5 structure - get with perks if exchange off DSB }) 3. e4 { usually dxe5 is played } 3... dxc4 4. Be3 Nf6 (4... exd4 5. Bxd4 (5. Qxd4 Qxd4 6. Bxd4 Nc6 $17) 5... Nc6 $17) 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. d5 Ne7 { by transposition to Ivanchuk vs Woff game } 7. Bxc4 Ng6 8. f3 Bd6 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. Nge2 a6 11. Bb3 b5 12. a4 O-O 13. O-O Qe7 14. Rac1 Nh5 15. g3 h6 16. Bc2 Rab8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra1 Ra8 19. Bd3 Bb4 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Qc2 Bc5 22. Nd1 Bd6 23. Nf2 Nhf4 24. Rc1 (24. gxf4 exf4 25. Bc1 Nh4 26. Kh1 (26. Bxf4 Bxf4 27. Nxf4 Qg5+ 28. Ng4 Qxf4 29. Qf2 Ng6 $17) 26... Nxf3 $10) 24... Qg5 25. Kh1 Qh5 (25... Nxe2 26. Bxg5 $16) 26. Ng1 Nxd3 27. Nxd3 f5 28. Nc5 Bc8 29. Rf1 Ne7 30. Qd3 fxe4 31. fxe4 Qg6 32. Kg2 Kh7 33. Nf3 Ng8 34. Nh4 Qg4 35. Nf5 Nf6 36. h3 { Game adjourned } 36... Qg6 37. Ne6 { In the Ivanchuk vs Wolff game g4 was played with draw in 72 moves } 37... Ra4 38. b3 Rxe4 39. Nxd6 Bxe6 (39... cxd6 40. Nf8+ Kg8 41. Nxg6 $16) 40. dxe6 cxd6 41. e7 d5 (41... Nh5 42. Rf8 Nf4+ 43. Bxf4 exf4 44. e8=Q Rxe8 45. Qxg6+ Kxg6 46. Rxe8 $16) 42. Bc5 Qe8 43. Qf3 Qc6 { mistake } (43... Kg8 44. Qxf6 gxf6 45. Rxf6 Qf7 $17 { black winning here with help of King }) 44. b4 Qe8 { Draw?! } 45. Qf5+ Kh8 (45... Kg8 46. Qe6+ Kh7 47. Rxf6 gxf6 48. Qxf6 d4 (48... Qh5 49. g4 Re2+ 50. Kg3 Qe8 51. Qf5+ Kg7 52. Qf8+ Qxf8 53. exf8=Q+ $16) 49. Qf5+ Qg6 50. Qxg6+ Kxg6 51. e8=Q+) 46. Qxf6 gxf6 47. Rxf6 Qh5 (47... Re2+ 48. Kf1 Kg7 49. Rf8 Qh5 50. e8=Q $16) 48. Rf8+ Kg7 49. e8=Q Re2+ 50. Kf1 { strongest move } (50. Kh1 Qxh3+ 51. Kg1 Qg2#) 50... Qxh3+ (50... Qxe8 51. Rxe8 $16) 51. Kxe2 Qg2+ 52. Rf2 Qe4+ 53. Kd2 { "It is your game" - and offers King and a respectful hug after } 1-0


