1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... Nc6 { Livestream video of this game can be found here : https://www.reddit.com/r/kingscrusher/comments/ai1mkr/annotated_game_from_reddit_january_tournament/
Technically this is "B00 KP, Nimzovich defence" as in Aron Nimzovich, one of my favourite hyper modernists who wrote the classic "My System". But I like to call this for short "The Tango" and have memories of "The Scent of a woman" one of my favourite films where it Al Pacino saids: "If you get all tangled up, just tango on.”.
The Tango is one of my favourite surprise opening weapons in blitz chess. One of the key ideas positionally is to tempt pawns onto light squares - so pawns on d5 and e4 have corresponding dark squared weaknesses. This means that later if White is tempted to have such pawns, the Dark squared bishop is often really good.
The Tango does give rise to some trap lines for extra quick wins. My favourite trap answer on Quora is one of my highest voted answers and features a nice Tango trap: https://www.quora.com/What-is-your-favorite-trap-in-your-favorite-Chess-opening - the "Tango" or sometimes called "The Queen Knights Tango" has generally scored well for me in lichess tournaments. } { [%clk 0:01:30] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2... e5 { [%clk 0:01:30] } 3. dxe5 { I would have preferred a Knights Tango with white playing d5 Nce7 and then Ng6 with bc5 in mind. He has thwarted my arch dark square strategy already! Oh well - plan B. An alternative for White is Nf3 but I am getting used to the Scotch game positions now and rather like the continuation Nf3 exd4 Nxd4 Bb4+ c3 and Magnus Carlsen's secret pet Be7 instead of Bc5 which takes the Scotch specialist a litle bit out of their top studied territory. } { [%clk 0:03:02] } 3... f6 { Trying to maximise my piece activity which i find is effective for these multi-round as many games as you can play tournaments to maximise chance of a quick win. Analysing recent crushing games of Stockfish it seems also Stockfish does very well sometimes with piece pressure from gambits against leela Chess. I think tactically oriented players in blitz can do well with gambits for piece pressure which would give rise often to concrete tactical opportunities.
I have often thought of f6 as a bit like c3 in the Smith morra gambit - trying to accelerate development. Of course it weakens the c4-g8 diagonal but on the upside when castling, there is by default an active rook on f8 and a semi-open file to play with. } { [%clk 0:01:29] } 4. exf6 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 4... Nxf6 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 5. Bd3 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 5... Bc5 { At least my dark squared bishop is active here and I can look forward to the semi-open f-file. It eyes of course f2 which can become a signficant "soft spot" around White's King. } { [%clk 0:01:28] } 6. Ne2 { Ne2 seems a little passive and neglects the h2 soft spot a little. I remember a Nezhmetdinov game brilliancy where Ne2 was played and Nez launched a pretty direct attack: http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1111459 - which I video annotated here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OIjDvqCVftw - sometimes direct play against Soft spots can be justified. } { [%clk 0:03:01] } 6... d6 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 7. O-O { [%clk 0:03:03] } 7... Ng4 { Pretty direct. But sometimes direct and crude also can equal "effective". One has to know the difference and if it is justified to play in such a direct way.
Here I go straight in rather crudely for the h2 and f2 softspots. But my opponent's Ne2 gives an open invitation for Qh4 as well and also I am eyeing f2 as well of course. In fact I wasn't entirely aware of f2 being a great target until i realised later Nxf2 was possible. } { [%cal Gf6g4,Gc5f2] [%clk 0:01:27] } 8. b4 { Counter pawn sacrifice! } { [%clk 0:02:29] } 8... Bb6 { I would like to keep my bishop targeted at f2. That pawn on b4 proves handy later in the variations though for potentially creating the prospect of c4-c5 to trap the b6 bishop. } { [%clk 0:01:23] } 9. c4 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 9... Qh4 { Pretty direct stuff here but Ne2 was an invitation for this. My queen threatens Qxh2 mate, and also hits the f2 pawn. } { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gg4h2,Gh4f2,Gb6f2] [%clk 0:01:22] } 10. h3 { [%clk 0:02:21] } 10... Nxf2 { Yes this does look rather good - and I was a little surprised this was possible against such a high rated opponent. } { [%clk 0:01:19] } 11. Rxf2 { The best practical decision. } { [%clk 0:02:17] } 11... Qxf2+ { [%clk 0:01:17] } 12. Kh2 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 12... Ne5 { Introduces Nf3+ which could be handy. However I am setting up some tactical liabilities which I am a little oblvious too shortly. } { [%clk 0:01:09] } (12... Bg4! 13. Bg5 Bxe2 { Weakens d4 square and aims to exploit unprotected rook on a1 } 14. Bxe2 Qd4 15. Nd2 (15. Qxd4 Bxd4 $17) 15... Qe5+ { Wow, some interesting tactics lurk beneath this game :) }) 13. Ng3 { [%cal Ge5f3] [%clk 0:02:14] } 13... O-O? { Now Rf3 is handy and dangerous which would fork d3 and g3 } { [%clk 0:00:59] } (13... Nf3+! { This would have ended the game a lot quicker :) It is good to check for forcing moves - even seemingly outrageous and silly ones at first glance. But if the Queen takes on f3 then there is Qg1 checkmate. } 14. Kh1 (14. Qxf3 Qg1# { [%cal Gb6g1,Ga1g1] }) 14... Ne1 { g2 is very difficult to defend here from the threat Qxg2 mate } 15. Qh5+ { A spite check only } 15... g6 16. Qxg6+ { To delay Qxg2 only } 16... hxg6 17. h4 Qg1#) 14. Be2 { Parrys Rf3 } { [%clk 0:01:54] } 14... Be6 { My rooks are connected now "Hello! Hello!" the rooks say to each other :) } { [%clk 0:00:50] } (14... Rf3! 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Ng4+ 17. hxg4 (17. Kh1 Rxh3+ 18. gxh3 Qh2# { No i did not see this variation either :) }) 17... Qh4#) 15. Bb2 { Now I completely miss whites threat here of Bxe5 and c5. Also c5 as well for winning e5. The Knight on e5 although central is also a tactical liability in its own right. Such is the cruel duality of Chess! What looks good visually can be bad concretely ! } { [%clk 0:01:52] } 15... Rae8? { Whoops! } { [%clk 0:00:47] } (15... Nf3+ { This apparently is a really crushing tactical move. One of the ideas is the Queen on d1 has to hold g1 against Qg1 mate. It was even more crushing earlier when Bxf3 was not available. } 16. Bxf3 Rxf3 17. Qxf3 (17. Nf5 Rxh3+ 18. Kxh3 g5 19. Qh5 Be3 20. Be5 dxe5 21. Qg4 Bf4 22. Nd2 h5 23. Qxh5 Qg3# { This variation is difficult to calculate with just 1.5 minutes. It is nice to see the kind of resources that lurk in games though with computer analysis :) }) 17... Qg1#) 16. Bxe5 { My dark squared bishop has no counterpart now. However there is a great concrete point about this that seemingly both me and the opponent misses! } { [%clk 0:01:53] } 16... dxe5 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc4c6] [%clk 0:00:46] } 17. Nc3? { Big mistake - c5 was much stronger and would have totally justified Bxe5. } { [%clk 0:01:54] } (17. c5 { this does look rather strong :) } 17... Qf4 18. cxb6 Rd8 19. Qc2 axb6 { White is fine here }) 17... Bd4 { My bishop now is great in the center. I am back in good shape here. } { [%clk 0:00:44] } 18. Rc1 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 18... Rf6 { With ideas of rg6. I enjoy rook lifts. Leela has done a lot of them in her attacking chess games :) } { [%clk 0:00:43] } 19. Nd5 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 19... Bxd5 { [%clk 0:00:42] } 20. cxd5 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 20... Rg6 { [%clk 0:00:41] } 21. Qd3 { [%clk 0:01:48] } 21... Qf4 { With the idea of celebrating the pin with bf2. It is difficult to unpin here. I thought I was doing quite well here. } { [%clk 0:00:30] } 22. Rf1 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 22... Bf2 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 23. Rxf2 { [%clk 0:01:42] } 23... Qxf2 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 24. Bh5 { I can simplify now which is helpful when very short of time. I have 29 seconds to convert this to a win. My opponent I believe also has increment luxury - the price of the berserk is also that I have no increment. Can I do this in less than 30 seconds now? } { [%clk 0:01:43] } 24... Rxg3 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 25. Qxg3 { [%clk 0:01:45] } 25... Qxg3+ { [%clk 0:00:25] } 26. Kxg3 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 26... g6 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 27. Bg4 { [%clk 0:01:48] } 27... Kf8 { Good in general to keep the King on dark squares away from the light squared bishop. } { [%clk 0:00:23] } 28. Bd7 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 28... Rd8 { In fact, good to keep all one's "valuables" on dark squares now in general. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 29. Ba4 { [%clk 0:01:50] } 29... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 30. Kf3 { [%clk 0:01:51] } 30... Kd6 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 31. Ke2 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 31... a6 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 32. Bb3 { [%clk 0:01:54] } 32... b5 { Start fixing down pawns is often a good idea in endgames. Michael Adams got the nickname "The Spider" because he often ran his opponents out of counterplay. I noticed a lot of the time even in endgames, Adams would start fixing the opponent's pawns on every sector of the board, in a spider like manner, to remove counterplay. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 33. a3 { [%clk 0:01:55] } 33... c6 { Undermining d5 can help try and overload the White squared bishop if it has to nanny d5. } { [%clk 0:00:19] } 34. dxc6 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 34... Kxc6 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 35. Bd5+ { [%clk 0:01:58] } 35... Kd6 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 36. Bb3 { [%clk 0:01:59] } 36... Rc8 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 37. Kd2 { [%clk 0:02:00] } 37... Rf8 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 38. Ke2 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 38... Rc8 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 39. Kd2 { [%clk 0:02:02] } 39... Ra8 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 40. Bd5 { [%clk 0:02:02] } 40... Ra7 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 41. Bg8 { [%clk 0:02:03] } 41... a5 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 42. bxa5 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 42... Rxa5 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 43. Bxh7 { [%clk 0:02:06] } 43... g5 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 44. g3 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 44... Rxa3 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 45. h4 { [%clk 0:02:06] } 45... gxh4 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 46. gxh4 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 46... Rh3 { This is starting to look good with my passed b pawn on the way. It is a relief to remove this passed pawn. } { [%clk 0:00:10] } 47. Bg6 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 47... Rxh4 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 48. Kc3 { [%clk 0:02:09] } 48... Rf4 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 49. Bf5 { [%clk 0:02:10] } 49... Kc5 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 50. Kd3 { [%clk 0:02:12] } 50... b4 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 51. Ke3 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 51... b3 { With 7 seconds to go, I was getting a little concerned about running out of time here :) } { [%clk 0:00:08] } 52. Be6 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 52... Kb4 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 53. Kd3 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 53... Ka3 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 54. Bxb3 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 54... Kxb3 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 55. Ke3 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 55... Kc4 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 56. Kd2 { [%clk 0:02:17] } 56... Kd4 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 57. Ke2 { [%clk 0:02:19] } 57... Kxe4 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 58. Kd2 { [%clk 0:02:21] } 58... Kd4 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 59. Kc2 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 59... Re4 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 60. Kd2 { [%clk 0:02:25] } 60... Re3 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 61. Kc2 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 61... Rd3 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 62. Kb2 { I could see my moves are not too complex now - just queen and then use checks to avoid stalemate hopefully. } { [%clk 0:02:28] } 62... e4 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 63. Kc2 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 63... e3 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 64. Kb2 { [%clk 0:02:32] } 64... e2 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 65. Kc2 { [%clk 0:02:34] } 65... e1=Q { [%clk 0:00:02] } 66. Kb2 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 66... Qc3+ { [%clk 0:00:02] } 67. Kb1 { [%clk 0:02:37] } 67... Rd1+ { [%clk 0:00:02] } 68. Ka2 { [%clk 0:02:39] } 68... Ra1# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { Phew! Made it just in time with one second to go. I exclaimed "On the buzzer!" in the livestream! :) Having now seen the variations behind the scenes, I can see how more accurate calculation of forcing move opportunities can lead to far conciser games :) } { [%clk 0:00:01] } 0-1


